{"title_page": "Wet market", "text_new": "{{short description|Market selling perishable goods, including meat, produce, and food animals}}\n{{Chinese VANDALISM\n|pic=WetmarketHK.jpg VANDALISM\n|piccap=A wet market in Hong Kong VANDALISM\n|picsize=250pxVANDALISM\n|s=[[wiktionary:\u50b3\u7d71|\u4f20\u7edf]][[wiktionary:\u5e02\u573a|\u5e02\u573a]]VANDALISM\n|t=[[wiktionary:\u50b3\u7d71|\u50b3\u7d71]][[wiktionary:\u5e02\u5834|\u5e02\u5834]]VANDALISM\n|p=chu\u00e1nt\u01d2ng sh\u00ecch\u01ceng\n|j=cyun<sup>4</sup> tung<sup>2</sup> si<sup>5</sup> coeng<sup>4</sup>\n|l=traditional market\n|showflag=pj\n|s2=[[wiktionary:\u8857\u5e02|\u8857\u5e02]]\n|t2=[[wiktionary:\u8857\u5e02|\u8857\u5e02]]\n|j2=gaai<sup>1</sup> si<sup>5</sup>\n|l2=street market\n|ci2={{IPAc-yue|g|aai|1|.|s|i|5}}\n}}\n\n<!-- \"\u8857\u5e02\" only means \"wet market\" in Cantonese, so pinyin here is unnecessary. -->\nA '''wet market''' (also called a '''public market''')<ref name=\"ZSCSH\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhong|first=Taiyang|last2=Si|first2=Zhenzhong|last3=Crush|first3=Jonathan|last4=Scott|first4=Steffanie|last5=Huang|first5=Xianjin|year=2019|title=Achieving urban food security through a hybrid public-private food provisioning system: the case of Nanjing, China|journal=Food Security|language=en|volume=11|issue=5|pages=1071\u20131086|doi=10.1007/s12571-019-00961-8|issn=1876-4517}}</ref><ref name=\"Morales-2009\">{{Cite journal|last=Morales|first=Alfonso|year=2009|title=Public Markets as Community Development Tools|journal=Journal of Planning Education and Research|language=en|volume=28|issue=4|pages=426\u2013440|doi=10.1177/0739456X08329471|issn=0739-456X}}</ref><ref name=\"Morales-2011\">{{Cite journal|last=Morales|first=Alfonso|year=2011|title=Marketplaces: Prospects for Social, Economic, and Political Development|journal=Journal of Planning Literature|language=en|volume=26|issue=1|pages=3\u201317|doi=10.1177/0885412210388040|issn=0885-4122}}</ref> is a [[marketplace]] selling fresh meat, fish, [[greengrocer|produce]], and other perishable goods as distinguished from \"dry markets\" that sell durable goods such as fabric and electronics.<ref>Wholesale Markets: Planning and Design Manual (Fao Agricultural Services Bulletin) (No 90)</ref><ref name=\"OED\">{{cite web |url=https://www.oed.com/view/Entry/227970 |title=wet, adj. |work=[[Oxford English Dictionary]] |quote=wet market ''n. South-East Asian'' a market for the sale of fresh meat, fish, and produce |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"brown\">{{Cite journal|last=Brown|first=Allison|year=2001|title=Counting Farmers Markets|journal=Geographical Review|volume=91|issue=4|pages=655\u2013674|doi=10.2307/3594724|jstor=3594724}}</ref> Not all wet markets sell live animals, but the term wet market is sometimes used to signify a live animal market in which vendors slaughter animals upon customer purchase.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Woo|first=Patrick CY|last2=Lau|first2=Susanna KP|last3=Yuen|first3=Kwok-yung|year=2006|title=Infectious diseases emerging from Chinese wet-markets: zoonotic origins of severe respiratory viral infections|journal=Current Opinion in Infectious Diseases|language=en|volume=19|issue=5|pages=401\u2013407|doi=10.1097/01.qco.0000244043.08264.fc|pmid=16940861|issn=0951-7375}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Wan|first=X.F.|year=2012|title=Lessons from Emergence of A/Goose/Guangdong/1996-Like H5N1 Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza Viruses and Recent Influenza Surveillance Efforts in Southern China: Lessons from Gs/Gd/96-like H5N1 HPAIVs|journal=Zoonoses and Public Health|language=en|volume=59|pages=32\u201342|doi=10.1111/j.1863-2378.2012.01497.x|pmc=4119829|pmid=22958248}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN-not\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/14/asia/china-wet-market-coronavirus-intl-hnk/index.html |title=China's wet markets are not what some people think they are |first1=Ben |last1=Westcott |first2=Serenitie |last2=Wang|publisher=CNN |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Wet markets are common in many parts of the world,<ref name=\"nw\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/peta-launches-petition-close-wet-markets-coronavirus-1494803 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |title= PETA launches petition to shut down live animal markets that breed diseases like COVID-19 |first=Khaleda |last=Rahman |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Reardon|first=Thomas|last2=Timmer|first2=C. Peter|last3=Minten|first3=Bart|date=2012-07-31|title=Supermarket revolution in Asia and emerging development strategies to include small farmers|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=109|issue=31|pages=12332\u201312337|doi=10.1073/pnas.1003160108|issn=0027-8424|pmc=3412023|pmid=21135250|bibcode=2012PNAS..10912332R}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/29/800725826/why-wet-markets-are-the-perfect-place-to-spread-disease|title=Why Wet Markets Are The Perfect Place To Spread Disease|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"vox-samuel\">{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2020/4/15/21219222/coronavirus-china-ban-wet-markets-reopening |publisher=[[Vox]] |title=The coronavirus likely came from China\u2019s wet markets. They\u2019re reopening anyway. |last=Samuel |first=Sigal |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/> notably in [[China]] and [[Southeast Asia]], and include a wide variety of markets, such as [[farmers' market]]s, [[fish market]]s, and [[Wildlife trade|wildlife market]]s.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/> They often play critical roles in urban [[food security]] due to factors of pricing, freshness of food, social interaction, and local cultures.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"Morales-2009\" /><ref name=\"Morales-2011\" />\n\nNot all wet markets carry living animals or wildlife products,<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/><ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/> but those that do have been linked to outbreaks of [[zoonotic disease]]s, with one such market believed to have played a role in the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Wet markets were banned from holding wildlife in China in 2003, after the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak]] which was directly tied to those practices.<ref name=\":2\" /> Such regulations were lifted before being put into place again in 2020,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/74f1b26e-53c0-11ea-90ad-25e377c0ee1f|title=Coronavirus piles pressure on China's exotic animal trade|last=Yu|first=Sun|last2=Liu|first2=Xinning|date=2020-02-23|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> with other countries proposing similar bans.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eba067c4-69ce-11ea-800d-da70cff6e4d3|title=The economic case for ending wildlife trade hits home in Vietnam|last=Reed|first=John|date=2020-03-19|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> Media reports that fail to distinguish between all wet markets from those with live animals or wildlife, as well as insinuations of fostering [[wildlife smuggling]], have been blamed for fueling [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|xenophobia related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/><ref name=\"FP\">{{cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/coronavirus-covid19-dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-virus/ |publisher=[[Foreign Policy]] |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Coronavirus |last=Palmer |first=James |date=27 January 2020 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vox-samuel\"/>\n\n== Background ==\n\n===Terminology===\nThe term \"wet market\" came into common use in Singapore in the early 1970s when the government used it to distinguish such traditional markets from the [[supermarket]]s that had become popular there.<ref name=\"Tan_p3\">{{cite book|last=Tan|first=Alvin|url=https://www.nhb.gov.sg/~/media/nhb/files/resources/publications/ebooks/nhb_ebook_wet_markets.pdf|title=Wet Markets|publisher=National Heritage Board|year=2013|series=Community Heritage Series|volume=II|location=Singapore|page=3|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> The term was added to the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' (''OED'') in 2016, as a term used throughout Southeast Asia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://public.oed.com/updates/march-2016-update-new-singapore-english-words/|title=New Singapore English words|date=2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> The ''OED'''s earliest cited use of the term is from ''[[The Straits Times]]'' of Singapore in 1978.<ref name=\"OED\" />\n\nThe \"wet\" in \"wet market\" refers to the constantly<ref name=Burton/> wet floors due to the melting of ice used to keep food from spoiling,<ref name=\"Tan_p3\" /><ref name=\"Reuters\" /> the washing of meat and seafood stalls and the spraying of fresh produce.<ref name=Burton>{{cite book|last=Burton|first=Dawn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hiFxfmZteFgC|title=Cross-Cultural Marketing: Theory, Practice and Relevance|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=2008|isbn=9781134060177|page=146}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN-not\"/><ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/>\n\nThe term \"public market\" may be synonymous with \"wet market\",<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"Morales-2009\" /><ref name=\"Morales-2011\" /> although it may sometimes refer exclusively to state-owned and community-owned wet markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"Morales-2009\" /><ref name=\"Morales-2011\" /> Wet markets may also be called \"fresh food markets\" and \"good food markets\" when referring to markets consisting of numerous competing vendors primarily selling fruits and vegetables.<ref name=\"brown\" /> The term \"wet market\" is frequently used to signify a live animal market that sells directly to consumers,<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> although the terms are not synonymous.<ref name=\"vox-samuel\"/>\n\n===Types===\nThe term \"wet market\", which specifies markets that sell fresh produce and meat, includes a broad variety of markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\" /> Wet markets can be categorized according to their ownership structure ([[Privately held company|privately owned]], [[State-owned enterprise|state-owned]], or [[Community ownership|community-owned]]), scale ([[Wholesaling|wholesale]] or [[retail]]), and produce (vegetables, slaughtered meat, live animals).<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\" /> They can be further subcategorized based on whether the meat inventory originates from [[Domestication of animals|domesticated]] or [[wildlife|wild animal]]s.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\" />\n\nTraditional wet markets are typically housed in temporary sheds, open-air sites,<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"NR-shaheen\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/03/the-chinese-wild-animal-industry-and-wet-markets-must-go/ |publisher=[[National Review]] |last=Shaheen |first=Therese |title=The Chinese Wild-Animal Industry and Wet Markets Must Go |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"HLZRZC\"/><ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/apr/15/mixed-with-prejudice-calls-for-ban-on-wet-markets-misguided-experts-argue-coronavirus |title=\u2018Mixed with prejudice\u2019: calls for ban on \u2018wet\u2019 markets misguided, experts argue |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |first=Michael |last=Standaert |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> or partially open commercial complexes,<ref name=\"ZCZ\">{{Cite journal |last=Zhong |first=Shuru |last2=Crang |first2=Mike |last3=Zeng |first3=Guojun |year=2020 |title=Constructing freshness: the vitality of wet markets in urban China |url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s10460-019-09987-2 |journal=Agriculture and Human Values |language=en |volume=37 |issue=1 |pages=175\u2013185 |doi=10.1007/s10460-019-09987-2 |issn=0889-048X}}</ref><ref name=\"vox-samuel\"/> while modern wet markets are housed in buildings often equipped with improved ventilation, freezing, and refrigeration facilities.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"Nikkei\" /><ref name=\"focus\" />\n\n===Economic role===\nWet markets are less dependent on imported goods than supermarkets due to their smaller volumes and lesser emphasis on consistency.<ref name=\"ATH-12\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq|title=Agricultural Trade Highlights|publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]]|year=1994|page=12}}</ref> Wet markets have been described as \"critical for ensuring urban [[food security]]\", particularly in Chinese cities.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /> The influence of wet markets on urban food security include food pricing and physical accessibility.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" />\n\nResearchers have highlighted the lower prices, greater freshness of food, negotiation opportunities, and social interaction spaces as key reasons for the persistence of wet markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"Reuters\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bougoure|first=Ursula|last2=Lee|first2=Bernard|year=2009|editor-last=Lindgreen|editor-first=Adam|title=Service quality in Hong Kong: wet markets vs supermarkets|journal=British Food Journal|language=en|volume=111|issue=1|pages=70\u201379|doi=10.1108/00070700910924245|issn=0007-070X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mele|first=Christopher|last2=Ng|first2=Megan|last3=Chim|first3=May Bo|year=2015|title=Urban markets as a 'corrective' to advanced urbanism: The social space of wet markets in contemporary Singapore|journal=Urban Studies|language=en|volume=52|issue=1|pages=103\u2013120|doi=10.1177/0042098014524613|issn=0042-0980}}</ref> The persistence of wet markets has also been attributed to \"culinary traditions that call for freshly slaughtered meat and fish as opposed to frozen meats\".<ref name=\"Reuters\" />\n\nIn [[developing country|developing countries]] with [[Agrarian society|agriculture-based economies]], fresh meat is mainly distributed through traditional wet markets or meat stalls.<ref name=\"FAO\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fao.org/ag/againfo/themes/en/meat/marketing.html |publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization|Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations]] |title=Fresh Meat |date=25 November 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Wet markets selling fresh meat are often attached to or located near [[Slaughterhouse|slaughter facilities]].<ref name=\"FAO\" />\n\n== Health concerns ==\n{{see also|Wildlife smuggling and zoonoses|Factory farming#Human health impact}}\nIf [[sanitation]] standards are not maintained, wet markets can spread [[disease]]. Those that carry live animals and wildlife are at especially high risk of transmitting [[zoonosis|zoonoses]]. Because of the openness, newly introduced animals may come in direct contact with sales clerks, butchers, and customers or to other animals which they would never interact with in the wild. This may allow for some animals to act as [[Host (biology)|intermediate hosts]], helping a disease spread to humans.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last=Greenfield|first=Patrick|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/06/ban-live-animal-markets-pandemics-un-biodiversity-chief-age-of-extinction|title=Ban wildlife markets to avert pandemics, says UN biodiversity chief|date=2020-04-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nDue to unhygienic sanitation standards and the connection to the spread of zoonoses and [[pandemic]]s, some have grouped wet markets together with [[Intensive animal farming|factory farming]] as major health hazards in China and across the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/04/chinas-wet-markets-americas-factory-farming-both-violate-moral-common-sense/|title=China's Wet Markets, America's Factory Farming|date=2020-04-09|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grain.org/en/article/6418-building-a-factory-farmed-future-one-pandemic-at-a-time|title=Building a factory farmed future, one pandemic at a time|website=www.grain.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sustainablefoodtrust.org/articles/one-welfare-and-covid-19/|title=Sustainable Food Trust|last=info@sustainablefoodtrust.org|first=Sustainable Food Trust-|website=Sustainable Food Trust|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref name=\"DavidFickling\"/>\n\n{{multiimage\n| direction = horizontal\n| align     = center\n\n| width1    = 300\n\n| width2    = 267\n\n| width3    = 231\n| image1    = Unsanitary Wet Market Chinatown Yangon.jpg\n| caption1  = A wet market in Chinatown of [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]].\n\n| image2    = Fowl cages at wet market in Shenzhen, China.jpg\n| caption2  = Fowl cages at a wet market in [[Shenzen]], [[China]].\n| image3    = Rodents in cages outside wet market in Shenzhen, China.jpg\n| caption3  = Rodents at a wet market in Shenzhen\n| footer  = Unsanitary conditions with poor standards of hygiene and mixed produce packed tightly are known to spread disease.|\n}}\n\n=== Avian flu and SARS ===\n[[File:AntigenicShift_HiRes.svg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:AntigenicShift_HiRes.svg|thumb|[[Influenza]] virus can change by genetic reassortment as it travels between different hosts in its range. The presence of different [[Host (biology)#Host range|intermediate hosts]] in close proximity makes wet markets a high risk environment for such zoonoses.]]\nThe [[Influenza A virus subtype H5N1|H5N1 avian flu]], [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]], and [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] outbreaks can be traced to keeping live animals in wet markets where the potential for zoonotic transmission is greatly increased.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/02/05/802938289/new-coronavirus-wont-be-the-last-outbreak-to-move-from-animal-to-human|title=New Coronavirus 'Won't Be the Last' Outbreak to Move from Animal to Human|date=2020-02-05|accessdate=2020-02-29|publisher=[[NPR]]|department=Goats and Soda}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-01-24|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2020-02-29|location=London}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> In April 2020, scientist Peter Daszak described a Chinese wet market as follows: \"it is a bit of shock to go to a wildlife market and see this huge diversity of animals live in cages on top of each other with a pile of guts that have been pulled out of an animal and thrown on the floor [...] These are perfect places for viruses to spread.\"<ref>https://edition.cnn.com/2020/04/06/us/coronavirus-scientists-debate-origin-theories-invs/index.html</ref> In a 2007 study, Chinese scientists identified the presence of SARS-CoV-like viruses in [[horseshoe bats]] combined with unsanitary wildlife markets and the culture of eating exotic mammals in southern China as a \"time-bomb\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cheng|first=VC|year=2007|title=Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus as an Agent of Emerging and Reemerging Infection|journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews|volume=20|issue=4|pages=660\u201394|doi=10.1128/CMR.00023-07|pmc=2176051|pmid=17934078|quote=}}</ref> A 2018 study in [[Malaysia]] concluded that wet market workers were at greater risk for [[leptospirosis]] infections.<ref name=\"lepto\">{{Cite journal|last=Rahman|first=Mas Harithulfadhli Agus Ab|last2=Hairon|first2=Suhaily Mohd|last3=Hamat|first3=Rukman Awang|last4=Jamaluddin|first4=Tengku Zetty Maztura Tengku|last5=Shafei|first5=Mohd Nazri|last6=Idris|first6=Norazlin|last7=Osman|first7=Malina|last8=Sukeri|first8=Surianti|last9=Wahab|first9=Zainudin A.|last10=Mohammad|first10=Wan Mohd Zahiruddin Wan|last11=Idris|first11=Zawaha|year=2018|title=Seroprevalence and distribution of leptospirosis serovars among wet market workers in northeastern, Malaysia: a cross sectional study|journal=BMC Infectious Diseases|language=en|volume=18|issue=1|pages=569|doi=10.1186/s12879-018-3470-5|issn=1471-2334|pmc=6236877|pmid=30428852}}</ref>\n\nChinese environmentalists, researchers and state media have called for stricter regulation of exotic animal trade in the markets.<ref name=\"BloombergAus\" /> Medical experts [[Zhong Nanshan]], [[Guan Yi]] and [[Yuen Kwok-yung]] have also called for the closure of wildlife markets since 2010.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/comment/opinion/article/3047828/first-sars-now-wuhan-coronavirus-heres-why-china-should-ban-its|title=Wuhan coronavirus another reason to ban China's wildlife trade forever|date=2020-01-29|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n=== COVID-19 ===\n\nAmidst the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Chinese wet markets have been blamed for the outbreak.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|last=Spinney|first=Laura|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/28/is-factory-farming-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Is factory farming to blame for coronavirus?|date=2020-03-28|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712|quote=Most of the attention so far has been focused on the interface between humans and the intermediate host, with fingers of blame being pointed at Chinese wet markets and eating habits,...}}</ref> Some reports say wildlife markets in other countries of Asia,<ref name=\"sierraclub.org\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9now.nine.com.au/60-minutes/coronavirus-expert-shut-down-of-asias-wet-wildlife-markets-60-minutes/f7f7781f-8e44-4eb8-9704-804b1e1680ca|title=Coronavirus expert calls for shut down of Asia's wildlife markets|last=|first=|date=|website=Nine News Australia|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5797739/wild-animals-markets-coronavirus/|title=Wild Animal Markets Spark Fear in Fight Against Coronavirus|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Africa,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wildaid.org/africa-risks-virus-outbreak-from-wildlife-trade/|title=Africa Risks Virus Outbreak From Wildlife Trade|date=2020-02-28|website=WildAid|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"dailymaverick\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-02-a-sea-change-in-chinas-attitude-towards-wildlife-exploitation-may-just-save-the-planet/|title=A sea change in China's attitude towards wildlife exploitation may just save the planet|date=2020-03-02|newspaper=Daily Maverick|quote=Knights hoped China would also play a role to help \u201ccountries around the world. It\u2019s no good simply banning the trade in China. The same risks are very much out there in Asia as well as Africa.\u201d}}</ref><ref name=\"indiamongabay\">{{cite news|url=https://india.mongabay.com/2020/03/commentary-crackdown-on-wet-markets-and-illegal-wildlife-trade-could-prevent-the-next-pandemic/|title=Crackdown on wet markets and illegal wildlife trade could prevent the next pandemic|date=2020-03-25|newspaper=Mongabay India|quote=...what we do know is that wet markets such as Wuhan, and for that matter Agartala\u2019s Golbazar or the thousands such that exist in Asia and Africa allow for easy transmission of viruses and other pathogens from animals to humans.}}</ref> and in general all over the world are also similarly prone to health risks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20200326/fact-check-is-chinese-culture-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Fact-check: Is Chinese culture to blame for the coronavirus?|last=Mekelburg|first=Madlin|website=Austin American-Statesman|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> In April 2020, a group of US lawmakers, [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases|NIAID]] director [[Anthony Fauci]], [[United Nations Environment Programme|UNEP]] biodiversity chief Elizabeth Maruma Mrema, and [[China Biodiversity Conservation and Green Development Foundation|CBCGDF]] secretary general Zhou Jinfeng called for the global closure of wildlife markets due to the potential for zoonotic diseases and risk to [[endangered species]].<ref name=\"Politico\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Greenfield|first=Patrick|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/06/ban-live-animal-markets-pandemics-un-biodiversity-chief-age-of-extinction|title=Ban wildlife markets to avert pandemics, says UN biodiversity chief|date=April 6, 2020|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=April 7, 2020|location=}}</ref><ref name=\"abc-april\">{{cite news|last=Fortier-Bensen|first=Tony|url=https://abcnews4.com/news/local/sen-lindsey-graham-among-others-urge-global-ban-of-live-wildlife-markets-and-trade|title=Sen. Lindsey Graham, among others, urge global ban of live wildlife markets and trade|date=9 April 2020|accessdate=9 April 2020|publisher=[[ABC News]]}}</ref>\n\n==Around the world==\n\n=== China ===\n[[File:Seafood section of Sanqi Baihui Market, Hall 1 (20190519152946).jpg|thumb|Seafood section of Sanqi Baihui Market in [[Beijing]], [[China]]]]\nIn 2018, wet markets were noted to have remained the most prevalent food outlet in urban regions of China despite the rise of [[List of supermarket chains in China|supermarket chains]] since the 1990s.<ref name=\"sustainability-2018\">{{Cite journal |last=Zhong |first=Taiyang |last2=Si |first2=Zhenzhong |last3=Crush |first3=Jonathan |last4=Xu |first4=Zhiying |last5=Huang |first5=Xianjin |last6=Scott |first6=Steffanie |last7=Tang |first7=Shuangshuang |last8=Zhang |first8=Xiang |year=2018 |title=The Impact of Proximity to Wet Markets and Supermarkets on Household Dietary Diversity in Nanjing City, China |url=http://www.mdpi.com/2071-1050/10/5/1465 |journal=Sustainability |language=en |volume=10 |issue=5 |pages=1465 |doi=10.3390/su10051465 |issn=2071-1050|doi-access=free }}</ref> However, wet markets have been losing ground in popularity compared to supermarkets, despite the fact they may be seen as healthier and more sustainable.<ref name=\"DavidFickling\">{{Cite news|last=Fickling|first=David|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-04-04/coronavirus-closing-china-s-wet-markets-isn-t-a-solution|title=China Is Reopening Its Wet Markets. That's Good|date=3 April 2020|work=Bloomberg|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Reports suggest \"although there are well-managed, hygienic wet markets in and near bigger cities [in China], hygiene can be spotty, especially in smaller communities.\"<ref name=\"BloombergAus\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-08/wuhan-is-returning-to-life-so-are-its-disputed-wet-markets|title=Wuhan Is Returning to Life. So Are Its Disputed Wet Markets|date=8 April 2020|work=Bloomberg Australia-NZ|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  During the 2010s, \"smart markets\" equipped with e-payment terminals emerged as traditional wet markets faced increasing competition from discount stores.<ref name=\"SD-Hangzhou\" /> Wet markets also began facing competition from online grocery stores, such as [[Alibaba]]'s Hema stores.<ref name=\"CNN-not\"/>\n\nSince the 1990s, large cities across China have moved traditional outdoor wet markets to modern indoor facilities.<ref name=\"HLZRZC\">{{Cite journal |last=Hu |first=Dong-wen |last2=Liu |first2=Chen-xing |last3=Zhao |first3=Hong-bo |last4=Ren |first4=Da-xi |last5=Zheng |first5=Xiao-dong |last6=Chen |first6=Wei |year=2019 |title=Systematic study of the quality and safety of chilled pork from wet markets, supermarkets, and online markets in China |url=http://link.springer.com/10.1631/jzus.B1800273 |journal=Journal of Zhejiang University-SCIENCE B |language=en |volume=20 |issue=1 |pages=95\u2013104 |doi=10.1631/jzus.B1800273 |issn=1673-1581 |pmc=6331336 |pmid=30614233}}</ref><ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/> In 1999, all roadside markets in [[Hangzhou]] were banned and moved indoors.<ref name=\"SD-Hangzhou\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.shine.cn/feature/travel/1805315493/ |publisher=[[Shanghai Daily]] |title=Regeneration and reinvention of Hangzhou's wet markets |last=Jia |first=Shi |date=31 May 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> By 2014, all wet markets in [[Nanjing]] were moved indoors.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/>\n\nThe [[trade of wildlife]] is not common in China, particularly in large cities,<ref name=\"CNN-not\"/> and most wet markets in China do not contain live animals besides fish held in tanks.<ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/> However, some poorly-regulated Chinese wet markets provide outlets for the exotic wildlife trade industry that was estimated to be worth more than $73 billion in a 2017 Chinese government report.<ref name=\"CNN-not\"/><ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/> In 2003, wet markets across China were banned from holding wildlife after the 2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak, which was directly tied to such practices.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2014, live poultry was banned from all markets in Hangzhou due to the [[Influenza A virus subtype H7N9#Reported cases in 2013|H7N9 avian influenza outbreak]].<ref name=\"SD-Hangzhou\" /> Although the exact origin of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] is yet to be confirmed as of April 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg24532764-000-the-hunt-for-patient-zero-where-did-the-coronavirus-outbreak-start/|title=The hunt for patient zero: Where did the coronavirus outbreak start?|last=Lu|first=Donna|website=New Scientist|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebulletin.org/2020/03/experts-know-the-new-coronavirus-is-not-a-bioweapon-they-disagree-on-whether-it-could-have-leaked-from-a-research-lab/|title=Experts know the new coronavirus is not a bioweapon. They disagree on whether it could have leaked from a research lab|date=2020-03-30|website=Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Readfearn |first=Graham |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/09/how-did-the-coronavirus-start-where-did-it-come-from-how-did-it-spread-humans-was-it-really-bats-pangolins-wuhan-animal-market |title=How did coronavirus start and where did it come from? Was it really Wuhan's animal market?|date=2020-04-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> it has been linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in [[Wuhan]], [[China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uchicagomedicine.org/forefront/prevention-and-screening-articles/wuhan-coronavirus|title=COVID-19: What we know so far about the 2019 novel coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Following the outbreak, epidemiology experts from China and an number of animal welfare organizations called to ban the operation of wet markets selling wild animals for human consumption.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://cbc.ca/radio/thecurrent/the-current-for-feb-17-2020-1.5466207/experts-call-for-global-ban-on-live-animal-markets-wildlife-trade-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak-1.5466219|title=Experts call for global ban on live animal markets, wildlife trade amidst coronavirus outbreak|date=February 17, 2020|work=CBC|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak|publisher=The Guardian|date=24 January 2020|title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak|author=Sarah Boseley}}</ref>\n\nThe Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market was shut down on 1 January 2020.<ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/> The Chinese government subsequently announced a temporary ban on the sale of wild animal products at wet markets in late January 2020,<ref name=\"sierraclub.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sierraclub.org/sierra/china-could-end-global-trade-wildlife|title=China Could End the Global Trade in Wildlife|date=2020-03-26|website=Sierra Club|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"BI-ban\">{{citation|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/china-bans-wildlife-trade-consumption-coronavirus-2020-2|publisher=Business Insider|date=25 February 2020|title=China just banned the trade and consumption of wild animals. Experts think the coronavirus jumped from live animals to people at a market. |first=Aylin |last=Woodward |quote=A few weeks later, Chinese authorities temporarily banned the buying, selling, and transportation of wild animals in markets, restaurants, and online marketplaces across the country. Farms that breed and transport wildlife were also quarantined and shut down. The ban was expected to stay in place until the coronavirus epidemic ended, Xinhua News reported. But now it's permanent. |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/> and then a permanent ban in February 2020 with an exception for [[Traditional Chinese medicine|Traditional Chinese Medicine]] ingredients.<ref name=\"BI-ban\"/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gorman|first=James|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/27/science/coronavirus-pangolin-wildlife-ban-china.html|title=China's Ban on Wildlife Trade a Big Step, but Has Loopholes, Conservationists Say|date=2020-02-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> By 22 March 2020, at least 94% of the temporarily closed wet markets in China were reopened according to Chinese state-run media,<ref name=\"CNN-not\"/><ref name=\"DavidFickling\"/> leading to public criticism of the Chinese government's handling of wet markets by [[Anthony Fauci]] and [[Lindsey Graham]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=O'reilly|first=Andrew|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/lindsey-graham-asks-china-to-close-all-operating-wet-markets-after-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Lindsey Graham asks China to close 'all operating wet markets' after coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-04-02|work=Fox News|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bowden|first=John|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/490834-graham-asks-colleagues-to-support-call-for-china-to-close-wet-markets|title=Graham asks colleagues to support call for China to close wet markets|date=2020-04-02|work=The Hill|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/03/anthony-fauci-foreign-wet-markets-shutdown-162975 |title='Shut down those things right away': Calls to close 'wet markets' ramp up pressure on China |first=Quint |last=Forgey |date=3 April 2020 |work=Politico |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> As of April 2020, the Chinese government is drafting a permanent law to further tighten restrictions on wildlife trade.<ref name=\"CNN-not\"/><ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/>\n\n=== Hong Kong ===\n[[File:HK Bridges Street Market.JPG|thumb|The building that housed the former [[Bridges Street Market]] in [[Hong Kong]]]]\n[[File:Allmart (Shui Chuen O) Market.jpg|thumb|Shui Chuen O Market, a newer wet market under the ownership of the [[Hong Kong Housing Authority]]]]\n\nOn 16 May 1842, [[Central Market, Hong Kong|Central Market]] was opened in a central position on Queen's Road. In this market, people could find all kinds of meat, fruit and vegetables, poultry, salt fish, fresh fish, weighing rooms and money changers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/g1842/728468.pdf|title=The Friend Of China, and Hong Kong Gazette|date=1842-05-12|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 1920, the Reclamation Street Market was opened in [[Hong Kong]]. Due to structure problems, Reclamation Street Market was removed by the government in 1953.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u7b2c\u4e8c\u5c46\u5eff\u4e00\u4e16\u7d00\u83ef\u4eba\u5730\u5340\u6b77\u53f2\u6559\u80b2\u8ad6\u6587\u96c6|trans-title=Second Collection of Historical Education Papers on Chinese in the 21st Century |author=Bao Shaolin|publisher=Zhonghua Book Company (Hong Kong) Limited.|year=2012|language=Chinese|isbn=|location=|pages=332}}</ref> In 1957, Yau Ma Tei Street Market launched to replace the Reclamation Street Market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmis.hkpl.gov.hk/coverpage/-/coverpage/view?p_r_p_-1078056564_c=QF757YsWv59a9PNz3lScYjii24oro5jB&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_o=18&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_actual_q=%28%20%28%20allTermsMandatory%3A%28true%29%20OR+all_dc.title%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.creator%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.contributor%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.subject%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+fulltext%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.description%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20%29%20%29&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_order=desc&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_field=score&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_log=Y|title=\u6cb9\u9ebb\u5730\u65b0\u5efa\u8857\u5e02\u6628\u6668\u958b\u5e55\u5f8c\u71df\u696d|trans-title=Yau Ma Tei New Market opened after opening yesterday morning|language=Chinese|last=|first=|date=1957-11-02|work=Hong Kong Business Daily|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> There were fixed-pitch stalls which sold vegetables, fruits, seafood, beef, pork, and poultry. Also, there were stalls selling baby chickens, baby ducks, and three-striped box turtles as pets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hkmemory.hk/collections/oral_history/All_Items_OH/oha_70/records/index.html|title=Yau Ma Tei's wet markets in the early post-war period|date=2011-03-29|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, wet markets accounted for 70% of produce sales and 50% of meat sales in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"ATH-7\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq |title=Agricultural Trade Highlights |publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]] |year=1994 |page=7}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2000, many of Hong Kong's wet markets were managed by the [[Urban Council]] (within Hong Kong Island and Kowloon) or the [[Regional Council (Hong Kong)|Regional Council]] (in the [[New Territories]]). Since the disbandment of the two councils on 31 December 1999, these markets have been managed by the [[Food and Environmental Hygiene Department]] (FEHD) of the Hong Kong government.<ref name=\"2018fehd\" /><ref name=\"hk-audit\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aud.gov.hk/pdf_e/e51ch06sum.pdf |title=Report No. 51 of the Director of Audit \u2014 Chapter 6 |publisher=[[Audit Commission (Hong Kong)|Audit Commission]] |date=November 2008 |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 the government of Hong Kong proposed that all poultry should be slaughtered at central abattoirs to combat the spread of [[avian flu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.news.gov.hk/isd/ebulletin/en/category/issues/080614/html/080613en05005.htm |title=Central abattoir set for 2011 |website=Archive.news.gov.hk |date=2008-06-13 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the FEHD operated 74 wet markets housing approximately 13,070 stalls.<ref name=\"2018fehd\">{{cite web |title=Chapter IV \u2013 Environmental Hygiene |url=https://www.fehd.gov.hk/english/publications/annualrpt/2018/4.html |website=Annual Report 2018 |publisher=Food and Environmental Hygiene Department}}</ref> In addition, the [[Hong Kong Housing Authority]] operated 21 markets while private developers operated about 99 (in 2017).<ref name=\"legco2017\">{{cite web |title=Public markets |url=https://www.legco.gov.hk/research-publications/english/1617issh36-public-markets-20170927-e.pdf |publisher=Legislative Council Secretariat |date=27 September 2017}}</ref> As of 2018, planning is underway for new wet markets in the new towns at Tung Chung, Tin Shui Wai, Hung Shui Kiu, Tseung Kwan O, and Kwu Tung North.<ref name=\"2018fehd\" />\n\nIn Hong Kong, wet markets are most frequented by older residents, those with lower incomes, and domestic helpers who serve approximately 10 percent of Hong Kong's residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emeraldinsight.com/journals.htm?articleid=1412265&show=abstract |title=EmeraldInsight |website=EmeraldInsight.com |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Most [[Districts of Hong Kong|districts]] contain at least one wet market.<ref name=\"CNN-not\"/> Wet markets have become destinations for tourists to \"see the real Hong Kong\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://intransit.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/18/a-guide-to-hong-kongs-wet-markets/ | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | first=Sei | last=Chong | title=A Guide to Hong Kong's Wet Markets | date=18 March 2011|accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Many of the wet market buildings are owned by property investment firms and as a result the price of food can vary from market to market.<ref>{{cite news|author=Elmer W. Cagape |url=http://asiancorrespondent.com/64501/expensive-food-tung-chung-hk/ |title=Tung Chung town pays the most for food in Hong Kong |work=Asian Correspondent |date=2011-09-08 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Hong Kong's wet markets are known to use red lampshades to make the food look fresher.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u8d85\u5de8\u8857\u5e02\u71c8\u73fe\u8eab\u5546\u5834|trans-title=Super large wet market red lamps appears in shopping mall|url=http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|accessdate=19 November 2012|newspaper=Sharp Daily|date=14 September 2012|language=Chinese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108070308/http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|archive-date=8 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMarkets in Hong Kong are governed by the [[law of Hong Kong]], not [[Chinese law]]. Under the Slaughterhouse Regulation, the slaughtering of live bovine animals, swine, goats, sheep or soliped for human consumption must take place in a licenced slaughterhouse.<ref name=\"slaughterhousereg\">{{cite web |title=Cap. 132BU Slaughterhouses Regulation |url=https://www.elegislation.gov.hk/hk/cap132BU |website=Hong Kong e-Legislation |publisher=[[Department of Justice (Hong Kong)|Department of Justice]]}}</ref> None of the wet markets in Hong Kong hold wild or exotic animals.<ref name=\"CNN-not\"/>\n\nThe retail sale of live poultry in Hong Kong is permitted at licenced outlets only. At the end of 2016, there were 85 retail shops within public wet markets licenced to sell live poultry.<ref name=\"2017fhb\">{{cite web |title=Study on the Way Forward of Live Poultry Trade in Hong Kong |url=https://www.fhb.gov.hk/download/press_and_publications/consultation/170403_f_live_poultry_trade/e_consultancy_report_full.pdf |publisher=[[Food and Health Bureau]] |date=March 2017}}</ref> The FEHD has implemented a number of measures to reduce the risk of [[avian influenza]]. Regular inspections and cleaning take place, including nightly disinfection of each stall by external contractors. Stall owners selling live poultry are not allowed to keep the animals on the premises overnight; they must be slaughtered before 8:00 pm nightly.<ref name=\"2016fehd\">{{cite web |title=Faecal droppings of live poultry from Yan Oi Market in Tuen Mun tested positive of H7N9 virus |url=https://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201606/05/P201606050090.htm |publisher=Hong Kong Government |date=5 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Indonesia===\nTraditional wet markets (such as [[pasar pagi]]) are found across in [[Indonesia]] in both urban and rural areas. Wet markets face increasing competition from supermarkets as well as e-commerce companies like [[Shopee]] and [[Tokopedia]].<ref name=\"Nikkei\">{{cite news |url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Life-Arts/Life/Southeast-Asia-s-traditional-markets-hold-their-own |last=Roughneen |first=Simon |title=Southeast Asia's traditional markets hold their own |publisher=[[The Nikkei|Nikkei Asian Review]] |date=8 October 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In 2018, Indonesian wet market vendors that import goods expressed concerns over the decrease in value of the [[Indonesian rupiah]].<ref name=\"Nikkei\" />\n\nMany urban wet markets have undergone major renovations during the last decade, such as Jakarta's [[Mayestik Market]], to modernize them by introducing air conditioning, better ventilation, improved rubbish and liquid disposal systems, improved hygiene, and more safe and comfortable facilities for sellers.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} In 2018, the first modern wet market opened in [[Jakarta]] with a laboratory as well as freezing and refrigeration facilities.<ref name=\"Nikkei\" />\n\n===Malaysia===\nIn March 2020, the Malaysian government temporarily banned the operation of all wet markets (including ''[[pasar malam]]'' and ''pasar pagi'') as a [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia|national response to the coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"malaysia-ban\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/22/negri-hawkers-food-trucks-to-operate-7am-8pm-from-march-24 |publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]] |title=Negri hawkers, food trucks to operate 7am-8pm from March 24 |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\n[[File:Mercado 20 de noviembre - Oaxaca de Ju\u00e1rez - 10.jpg|thumb|Fresh meat section of the Mercado 20 de Noviembre in [[Oaxaca City|Oaxaca]], [[Mexico]]]]\nSome traditional [[Mexico|Mexican]] open-air markets called ''[[tianguis]]'', such as the Mercado Margarita Maza de Ju\u00e1rez in [[Oaxaca City|Oaxaca]], are separated into a wet market (''zona h\u00fameda'') and a dry market (''zona seca'').<ref name=\"imparcial\">{{cite news |url=https://imparcialoaxaca.mx/oaxaca/304648/central-de-abasto-bomba-de-tiempo-y-nido-de-delincuencia/ |title=Central de Abasto: bomba de tiempo y nido de delincuencia |publisher=[[El Imparcial (Oaxaca)]] |date=9 May 2019 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Philippines===\n{{Main|Palengke}}\nIn the [[Philippines]], wet markets are managed by [[cooperative]]s according to legislation such as the [[Philippine legal codes#Some other legal codes|Cooperatives Code]] (RA 7160) and the [[Agriculture and Fisheries Modernization Act of 1997|Agriculture and Fisheries Modernization Act]] (RA 8435).<ref name=\"PCIJ2002\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcij.org/imag/Society/palengke.html|title=Death of the Palengke|last=Pabico|first=Alecks P.|year=2002|publisher=Philippine Center for Investigative Journalism|accessdate=2009-01-05}}</ref> The Philippine government has control over the price of some commodities sold in palengkes, especially critical foods such as [[rice]].<ref name=\"Inq20080328\">{{cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/regions/view/20080328-127024/6-Cebu-rice-retailers-suspended-for-violations|title=6 Cebu rice retailers suspended for violations |last=Napallacan|first=Jhunnex|date=2008-03-28|work=Breaking News / Regions|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref><ref name=\"SS20070421\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/zam/2007/04/21/bus/food.agency.intensifies.palengke.watch..html|title=Food agency intensifies 'Palengke Watch'|last=Garcia|first=Bong|date=2007-04-21|publisher=Sun.Star Zamboanga|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, the digital wet market Palengke Boy was launched in [[Davao City]] to compete against traditional wet markets.<ref name=\"sunstar\">{{cite news |url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/1763228 |title=Teves: Palengke Boy: The family's digital wet market buddy |last=Huang-Teves |first=Janette |publisher=[[Sun.Star]] |date=7 September 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In March 2020, the [[Pasig]] local government launched a mobile wet market to ensure access to basic goods during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"abs-cbn\">{{cite news |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/26/20/taking-cue-from-pasig-valenzuela-eyes-own-market-on-wheels-amid-quarantine |title=Taking cue from Pasig, Valenzuela eyes own market-on-wheels amid quarantine |last=Domingo |first=Katrina |publisher=[[ABS-CBN]] |date=26 March 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Singapore===\n[[File:Wet market in Tekka Centre, Singapore - 20030228.jpg|thumb|Wet market in [[Tekka Centre|Tekka Market]], [[Singapore]]]]\nWet markets in [[Singapore]] are subsidized by the government.<ref name=\"Nikkei\" /> The [[Tekka Centre|Tekka Market]], [[Tiong Bahru#Tiong Bahru Market|Tiong Bahru Market]], and [[Chinatown, Singapore#Geography|Chinatown Complex Market]] are prominent wet markets containing seasonal fruit, fresh vegetables, imported beef, and live seafood.<ref name=\"cnn-sg\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/singapore-wet-market/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |title=Singapore wet markets: Reminder of bygone days |date=22 June 2015 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, the slaughter of animals was banned in 12 inner-city markets and 22 wet market centers in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RjxIAAAAYAAJ |title=U.S. Trade and Prospects: Dairy, livestock, and poultry products |year=1992 |publisher=The Service |author=United States. Foreign Agricultural Service. Dairy, Livestock, and Poultry Division, United States. World Agricultural Outlook Board |page=3}}</ref> In early 2020, the [[National Environment Agency]] issued advisories for \"high standards of hygiene and cleanliness\" for the 83 markets that it oversees in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore#Preventive measures|a response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|last=Chandran|first=Rina|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/southeast-asia-health-markets/traditional-markets-blamed-for-virus-outbreak-are-lifeline-for-asias-poor-idUSL8N2A5201|title=Traditional markets blamed for virus outbreak are lifeline for Asia's poor|date=7 February 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n===Taiwan===\nIn 1997, a report by the [[Taipei]] city government indicated that the city had 61 major wet markets with almost 10,000 registered vendors.<ref name=\"twt\">{{cite news |url=https://taiwantoday.tw/news.php?post=12589&unit=8,29,32,45 |title=Are Wet Markets Drying Up? |publisher=[[Taiwan Today]] |last=Trappey |first=Charles V. |date=1 March 1997 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The report also indicated that most of the city's wet markets were in serious need of repair and that almost 3,500 of the vendor stalls lay vacant.<ref name=\"twt\" />\n\nThe Nanmen Market in Taipei is a government-owned traditional wet market that was opened in 1907 during the [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|Japanese colonial rule]].<ref name=\"focus\">{{cite news |publisher=[[Focus Taiwan]] |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/business/201910060010 |title=Nanmen Market to close for renovation after 38 years |date=6 October 2019 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"twt\" /> The market building was demolished in October 2019 and the market temporarily relocated until its replacement modern 12-floor building is completed in 2022.<ref name=\"focus\" />\n\n===Thailand===\n{{multiimage\n|direction=horizontal\n|image1=Wet market Chiang Mai.jpg\n|image2=Wet market Chiang Mai 2.jpg\n|width1=130\n|width2=215\n|footer=A wet market in Chinatown, [[Chiang Mai]], Thailand, selling a variety of shellfish and turtles.}}\n\nWet markets are the dominant preferred venue for grocery shopping in [[Thailand]] due to the local importance of fresh food,<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=-A-7d-2VpwcC |page=295 |title= Consumer Behavior and Culture: Consequences for Global Marketing and Advertising  |first=Marieke |last=de Mooij |publisher=[[Chronicle Books]] |year=2003|isbn=9780761926689 }}</ref> as well as lower prices and familiarity with shopkeepers.<ref name=\"Nikkei\" />\n\n===Vietnam===\nIn 2017, there were approximately 9,000 wet markets, 800 supermarkets, 160 shopping malls and 1.3 million small family-owned stores across [[Vietnam]] according to government estimates.<ref name=\"vne\">{{cite news |url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/travel-life/a-hanoi-wet-market-at-the-crossroads-of-modernity-3588516.html |publisher=[[VnExpress]] |title=A Hanoi wet market at the crossroads of modernity |last=Yen |first=Bao |date=12 June 2017 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the [[Hanoi]] city government planned to renovate the city's wet markets and transform them into modern shopping malls.<ref name=\"vne\" /> The plan was met with resistance from wet market vendors in 2017 after significant declines in sales figures from other markets that were moved to the basements of high-end shopping centers.<ref name=\"vne\" />\n\nIn 2020, [[Prime Minister of Vietnam]] [[Nguy\u1ec5n Xu\u00e2n Ph\u00fac]] announced proposals to ban wildlife trade in Vietnam.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Media coverage==\n\n{{globalize section|date=April 2020}}\n<!-- This section is for content *about* media coverage of wet markets, not content *from* media coverage of wet markets -->\nChinese wet markets have been criticized in media outlets during the COVID-19 outbreak.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nIn [[Western media]] wet markets have been portrayed without distinguishing between general wet markets, live animal wet markets, and wildlife markets,<ref name=\"BloombergAus\" /> using montages of images from different markets across China without identifying locations.<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\">{{cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/why-shutting-down-chinese-wet-markets-could-be-a-terrible-mistake-130625|title=Why shutting down Chinese 'wet markets' could be a terrible mistake|last1=Lynteris|first1=Christos|last2=Fearnley|first2=Lyle|date=2 March 2020|publisher=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lat\">{{cite news|last=St. Cavendish|first=Christopher|url=https://www.latimes.com/food/story/2020-03-11/coronavirus-china-wet-markets|title=No, China's fresh food markets did not cause coronavirus|date=11 March 2020|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> Most wet markets in China do not sell wild animals.<ref name=\"DavidFickling\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radiichina.com/wet-markets-wild-animals-china/|title=No, You Won't Find \"Wild Animals\" in Most of China's Wet Markets|last=Bossons|first=Matthew|date=2020-02-25|website=RADII|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/> These depictions have been criticized as exaggerated and [[Orientalism|Orientalist]], and have been blamed for fueling [[Sinophobia]] and \"Chinese otherness\".<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\" /><ref name=\"lat\" /><ref name=\"FP\" />\n\nSince the outbreak of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], media reports urging for permanent blanket bans on all wet markets\u2014as opposed to solely live animal markets or wildlife markets\u2014have been criticized for undermining [[infection control]] needs to be specific about wildlife markets, such as the Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market.<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Artisanal food]]\n* [[Asian supermarket]]\n* [[Bazaar]]\n* [[Pasar malam]]\n* [[Souk]]\n* [[Ye wei]] (southern China)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Wet markets}}\n{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/gallery/2009/may/15/china-animalwelfare-cat | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Conservation (Environment), Wildlife (Environment), World news, China (News), Animal welfare (News), Food (impact of production on environment), Animals (News), Ethical and green living (Environment), Environment, Chinese food and drink, Asia Pacific (News) | date=15 May 2009}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:Food markets]]\n[[Category:Retail markets]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Market selling perishable goods, including meat, produce, and food animals}}\n{{Chinese\n|pic=WetmarketHK.jpg\n|piccap=A wet market in Hong Kong\n|picsize=250px\n|s=[[wiktionary:\u50b3\u7d71|\u4f20\u7edf]][[wiktionary:\u5e02\u573a|\u5e02\u573a]]\n|t=[[wiktionary:\u50b3\u7d71|\u50b3\u7d71]][[wiktionary:\u5e02\u5834|\u5e02\u5834]]\n|p=chu\u00e1nt\u01d2ng sh\u00ecch\u01ceng\n|j=cyun<sup>4</sup> tung<sup>2</sup> si<sup>5</sup> coeng<sup>4</sup>\n|l=traditional market\n|showflag=pj\n|s2=[[wiktionary:\u8857\u5e02|\u8857\u5e02]]\n|t2=[[wiktionary:\u8857\u5e02|\u8857\u5e02]]\n|j2=gaai<sup>1</sup> si<sup>5</sup>\n|l2=street market\n|ci2={{IPAc-yue|g|aai|1|.|s|i|5}}\n}}\n\n<!-- \"\u8857\u5e02\" only means \"wet market\" in Cantonese, so pinyin here is unnecessary. -->\nA '''wet market''' (also called a '''public market''')<ref name=\"ZSCSH\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhong|first=Taiyang|last2=Si|first2=Zhenzhong|last3=Crush|first3=Jonathan|last4=Scott|first4=Steffanie|last5=Huang|first5=Xianjin|year=2019|title=Achieving urban food security through a hybrid public-private food provisioning system: the case of Nanjing, China|journal=Food Security|language=en|volume=11|issue=5|pages=1071\u20131086|doi=10.1007/s12571-019-00961-8|issn=1876-4517}}</ref><ref name=\"Morales-2009\">{{Cite journal|last=Morales|first=Alfonso|year=2009|title=Public Markets as Community Development Tools|journal=Journal of Planning Education and Research|language=en|volume=28|issue=4|pages=426\u2013440|doi=10.1177/0739456X08329471|issn=0739-456X}}</ref><ref name=\"Morales-2011\">{{Cite journal|last=Morales|first=Alfonso|year=2011|title=Marketplaces: Prospects for Social, Economic, and Political Development|journal=Journal of Planning Literature|language=en|volume=26|issue=1|pages=3\u201317|doi=10.1177/0885412210388040|issn=0885-4122}}</ref> is a [[marketplace]] selling fresh meat, fish, [[greengrocer|produce]], and other perishable goods as distinguished from \"dry markets\" that sell durable goods such as fabric and electronics.<ref>Wholesale Markets: Planning and Design Manual (Fao Agricultural Services Bulletin) (No 90)</ref><ref name=\"OED\">{{cite web |url=https://www.oed.com/view/Entry/227970 |title=wet, adj. |work=[[Oxford English Dictionary]] |quote=wet market ''n. South-East Asian'' a market for the sale of fresh meat, fish, and produce |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"brown\">{{Cite journal|last=Brown|first=Allison|year=2001|title=Counting Farmers Markets|journal=Geographical Review|volume=91|issue=4|pages=655\u2013674|doi=10.2307/3594724|jstor=3594724}}</ref> Not all wet markets sell live animals, but the term wet market is sometimes used to signify a live animal market in which vendors slaughter animals upon customer purchase.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Woo|first=Patrick CY|last2=Lau|first2=Susanna KP|last3=Yuen|first3=Kwok-yung|year=2006|title=Infectious diseases emerging from Chinese wet-markets: zoonotic origins of severe respiratory viral infections|journal=Current Opinion in Infectious Diseases|language=en|volume=19|issue=5|pages=401\u2013407|doi=10.1097/01.qco.0000244043.08264.fc|pmid=16940861|issn=0951-7375}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Wan|first=X.F.|year=2012|title=Lessons from Emergence of A/Goose/Guangdong/1996-Like H5N1 Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza Viruses and Recent Influenza Surveillance Efforts in Southern China: Lessons from Gs/Gd/96-like H5N1 HPAIVs|journal=Zoonoses and Public Health|language=en|volume=59|pages=32\u201342|doi=10.1111/j.1863-2378.2012.01497.x|pmc=4119829|pmid=22958248}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN-not\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/14/asia/china-wet-market-coronavirus-intl-hnk/index.html |title=China's wet markets are not what some people think they are |first1=Ben |last1=Westcott |first2=Serenitie |last2=Wang|publisher=CNN |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Wet markets are common in many parts of the world,<ref name=\"nw\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/peta-launches-petition-close-wet-markets-coronavirus-1494803 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |title= PETA launches petition to shut down live animal markets that breed diseases like COVID-19 |first=Khaleda |last=Rahman |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Reardon|first=Thomas|last2=Timmer|first2=C. Peter|last3=Minten|first3=Bart|date=2012-07-31|title=Supermarket revolution in Asia and emerging development strategies to include small farmers|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=109|issue=31|pages=12332\u201312337|doi=10.1073/pnas.1003160108|issn=0027-8424|pmc=3412023|pmid=21135250|bibcode=2012PNAS..10912332R}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/29/800725826/why-wet-markets-are-the-perfect-place-to-spread-disease|title=Why Wet Markets Are The Perfect Place To Spread Disease|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"vox-samuel\">{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2020/4/15/21219222/coronavirus-china-ban-wet-markets-reopening |publisher=[[Vox]] |title=The coronavirus likely came from China\u2019s wet markets. They\u2019re reopening anyway. |last=Samuel |first=Sigal |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/> notably in [[China]] and [[Southeast Asia]], and include a wide variety of markets, such as [[farmers' market]]s, [[fish market]]s, and [[Wildlife trade|wildlife market]]s.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/> They often play critical roles in urban [[food security]] due to factors of pricing, freshness of food, social interaction, and local cultures.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"Morales-2009\" /><ref name=\"Morales-2011\" />\n\nNot all wet markets carry living animals or wildlife products,<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/><ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/> but those that do have been linked to outbreaks of [[zoonotic disease]]s, with one such market believed to have played a role in the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Wet markets were banned from holding wildlife in China in 2003, after the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak]] which was directly tied to those practices.<ref name=\":2\" /> Such regulations were lifted before being put into place again in 2020,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/74f1b26e-53c0-11ea-90ad-25e377c0ee1f|title=Coronavirus piles pressure on China's exotic animal trade|last=Yu|first=Sun|last2=Liu|first2=Xinning|date=2020-02-23|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> with other countries proposing similar bans.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eba067c4-69ce-11ea-800d-da70cff6e4d3|title=The economic case for ending wildlife trade hits home in Vietnam|last=Reed|first=John|date=2020-03-19|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> Media reports that fail to distinguish between all wet markets from those with live animals or wildlife, as well as insinuations of fostering [[wildlife smuggling]], have been blamed for fueling [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|xenophobia related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/><ref name=\"FP\">{{cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/coronavirus-covid19-dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-virus/ |publisher=[[Foreign Policy]] |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Coronavirus |last=Palmer |first=James |date=27 January 2020 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vox-samuel\"/>\n\n== Background ==\n\n===Terminology===\nThe term \"wet market\" came into common use in Singapore in the early 1970s when the government used it to distinguish such traditional markets from the [[supermarket]]s that had become popular there.<ref name=\"Tan_p3\">{{cite book|last=Tan|first=Alvin|url=https://www.nhb.gov.sg/~/media/nhb/files/resources/publications/ebooks/nhb_ebook_wet_markets.pdf|title=Wet Markets|publisher=National Heritage Board|year=2013|series=Community Heritage Series|volume=II|location=Singapore|page=3|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> The term was added to the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' (''OED'') in 2016, as a term used throughout Southeast Asia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://public.oed.com/updates/march-2016-update-new-singapore-english-words/|title=New Singapore English words|date=2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> The ''OED'''s earliest cited use of the term is from ''[[The Straits Times]]'' of Singapore in 1978.<ref name=\"OED\" />\n\nThe \"wet\" in \"wet market\" refers to the constantly<ref name=Burton/> wet floors due to the melting of ice used to keep food from spoiling,<ref name=\"Tan_p3\" /><ref name=\"Reuters\" /> the washing of meat and seafood stalls and the spraying of fresh produce.<ref name=Burton>{{cite book|last=Burton|first=Dawn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hiFxfmZteFgC|title=Cross-Cultural Marketing: Theory, Practice and Relevance|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=2008|isbn=9781134060177|page=146}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN-not\"/><ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/>\n\nThe term \"public market\" may be synonymous with \"wet market\",<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"Morales-2009\" /><ref name=\"Morales-2011\" /> although it may sometimes refer exclusively to state-owned and community-owned wet markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"Morales-2009\" /><ref name=\"Morales-2011\" /> Wet markets may also be called \"fresh food markets\" and \"good food markets\" when referring to markets consisting of numerous competing vendors primarily selling fruits and vegetables.<ref name=\"brown\" /> The term \"wet market\" is frequently used to signify a live animal market that sells directly to consumers,<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> although the terms are not synonymous.<ref name=\"vox-samuel\"/>\n\n===Types===\nThe term \"wet market\", which specifies markets that sell fresh produce and meat, includes a broad variety of markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\" /> Wet markets can be categorized according to their ownership structure ([[Privately held company|privately owned]], [[State-owned enterprise|state-owned]], or [[Community ownership|community-owned]]), scale ([[Wholesaling|wholesale]] or [[retail]]), and produce (vegetables, slaughtered meat, live animals).<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\" /> They can be further subcategorized based on whether the meat inventory originates from [[Domestication of animals|domesticated]] or [[wildlife|wild animal]]s.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\" />\n\nTraditional wet markets are typically housed in temporary sheds, open-air sites,<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"NR-shaheen\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/03/the-chinese-wild-animal-industry-and-wet-markets-must-go/ |publisher=[[National Review]] |last=Shaheen |first=Therese |title=The Chinese Wild-Animal Industry and Wet Markets Must Go |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"HLZRZC\"/><ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/apr/15/mixed-with-prejudice-calls-for-ban-on-wet-markets-misguided-experts-argue-coronavirus |title=\u2018Mixed with prejudice\u2019: calls for ban on \u2018wet\u2019 markets misguided, experts argue |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |first=Michael |last=Standaert |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> or partially open commercial complexes,<ref name=\"ZCZ\">{{Cite journal |last=Zhong |first=Shuru |last2=Crang |first2=Mike |last3=Zeng |first3=Guojun |year=2020 |title=Constructing freshness: the vitality of wet markets in urban China |url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s10460-019-09987-2 |journal=Agriculture and Human Values |language=en |volume=37 |issue=1 |pages=175\u2013185 |doi=10.1007/s10460-019-09987-2 |issn=0889-048X}}</ref><ref name=\"vox-samuel\"/> while modern wet markets are housed in buildings often equipped with improved ventilation, freezing, and refrigeration facilities.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"Nikkei\" /><ref name=\"focus\" />\n\n===Economic role===\nWet markets are less dependent on imported goods than supermarkets due to their smaller volumes and lesser emphasis on consistency.<ref name=\"ATH-12\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq|title=Agricultural Trade Highlights|publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]]|year=1994|page=12}}</ref> Wet markets have been described as \"critical for ensuring urban [[food security]]\", particularly in Chinese cities.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /> The influence of wet markets on urban food security include food pricing and physical accessibility.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" />\n\nResearchers have highlighted the lower prices, greater freshness of food, negotiation opportunities, and social interaction spaces as key reasons for the persistence of wet markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /><ref name=\"Reuters\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bougoure|first=Ursula|last2=Lee|first2=Bernard|year=2009|editor-last=Lindgreen|editor-first=Adam|title=Service quality in Hong Kong: wet markets vs supermarkets|journal=British Food Journal|language=en|volume=111|issue=1|pages=70\u201379|doi=10.1108/00070700910924245|issn=0007-070X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mele|first=Christopher|last2=Ng|first2=Megan|last3=Chim|first3=May Bo|year=2015|title=Urban markets as a 'corrective' to advanced urbanism: The social space of wet markets in contemporary Singapore|journal=Urban Studies|language=en|volume=52|issue=1|pages=103\u2013120|doi=10.1177/0042098014524613|issn=0042-0980}}</ref> The persistence of wet markets has also been attributed to \"culinary traditions that call for freshly slaughtered meat and fish as opposed to frozen meats\".<ref name=\"Reuters\" />\n\nIn [[developing country|developing countries]] with [[Agrarian society|agriculture-based economies]], fresh meat is mainly distributed through traditional wet markets or meat stalls.<ref name=\"FAO\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fao.org/ag/againfo/themes/en/meat/marketing.html |publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization|Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations]] |title=Fresh Meat |date=25 November 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Wet markets selling fresh meat are often attached to or located near [[Slaughterhouse|slaughter facilities]].<ref name=\"FAO\" />\n\n== Health concerns ==\n{{see also|Wildlife smuggling and zoonoses|Factory farming#Human health impact}}\nIf [[sanitation]] standards are not maintained, wet markets can spread [[disease]]. Those that carry live animals and wildlife are at especially high risk of transmitting [[zoonosis|zoonoses]]. Because of the openness, newly introduced animals may come in direct contact with sales clerks, butchers, and customers or to other animals which they would never interact with in the wild. This may allow for some animals to act as [[Host (biology)|intermediate hosts]], helping a disease spread to humans.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last=Greenfield|first=Patrick|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/06/ban-live-animal-markets-pandemics-un-biodiversity-chief-age-of-extinction|title=Ban wildlife markets to avert pandemics, says UN biodiversity chief|date=2020-04-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nDue to unhygienic sanitation standards and the connection to the spread of zoonoses and [[pandemic]]s, some have grouped wet markets together with [[Intensive animal farming|factory farming]] as major health hazards in China and across the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/04/chinas-wet-markets-americas-factory-farming-both-violate-moral-common-sense/|title=China's Wet Markets, America's Factory Farming|date=2020-04-09|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grain.org/en/article/6418-building-a-factory-farmed-future-one-pandemic-at-a-time|title=Building a factory farmed future, one pandemic at a time|website=www.grain.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sustainablefoodtrust.org/articles/one-welfare-and-covid-19/|title=Sustainable Food Trust|last=info@sustainablefoodtrust.org|first=Sustainable Food Trust-|website=Sustainable Food Trust|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref name=\"DavidFickling\"/>\n\n{{multiimage\n| direction = horizontal\n| align     = center\n\n| width1    = 300\n\n| width2    = 267\n\n| width3    = 231\n| image1    = Unsanitary Wet Market Chinatown Yangon.jpg\n| caption1  = A wet market in Chinatown of [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]].\n\n| image2    = Fowl cages at wet market in Shenzhen, China.jpg\n| caption2  = Fowl cages at a wet market in [[Shenzen]], [[China]].\n| image3    = Rodents in cages outside wet market in Shenzhen, China.jpg\n| caption3  = Rodents at a wet market in Shenzhen\n| footer  = Unsanitary conditions with poor standards of hygiene and mixed produce packed tightly are known to spread disease.|\n}}\n\n=== Avian flu and SARS ===\n[[File:AntigenicShift_HiRes.svg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:AntigenicShift_HiRes.svg|thumb|[[Influenza]] virus can change by genetic reassortment as it travels between different hosts in its range. The presence of different [[Host (biology)#Host range|intermediate hosts]] in close proximity makes wet markets a high risk environment for such zoonoses.]]\nThe [[Influenza A virus subtype H5N1|H5N1 avian flu]], [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]], and [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] outbreaks can be traced to keeping live animals in wet markets where the potential for zoonotic transmission is greatly increased.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/02/05/802938289/new-coronavirus-wont-be-the-last-outbreak-to-move-from-animal-to-human|title=New Coronavirus 'Won't Be the Last' Outbreak to Move from Animal to Human|date=2020-02-05|accessdate=2020-02-29|publisher=[[NPR]]|department=Goats and Soda}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-01-24|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2020-02-29|location=London}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> In April 2020, scientist Peter Daszak described a Chinese wet market as follows: \"it is a bit of shock to go to a wildlife market and see this huge diversity of animals live in cages on top of each other with a pile of guts that have been pulled out of an animal and thrown on the floor [...] These are perfect places for viruses to spread.\"<ref>https://edition.cnn.com/2020/04/06/us/coronavirus-scientists-debate-origin-theories-invs/index.html</ref> In a 2007 study, Chinese scientists identified the presence of SARS-CoV-like viruses in [[horseshoe bats]] combined with unsanitary wildlife markets and the culture of eating exotic mammals in southern China as a \"time-bomb\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cheng|first=VC|year=2007|title=Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus as an Agent of Emerging and Reemerging Infection|journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews|volume=20|issue=4|pages=660\u201394|doi=10.1128/CMR.00023-07|pmc=2176051|pmid=17934078|quote=}}</ref> A 2018 study in [[Malaysia]] concluded that wet market workers were at greater risk for [[leptospirosis]] infections.<ref name=\"lepto\">{{Cite journal|last=Rahman|first=Mas Harithulfadhli Agus Ab|last2=Hairon|first2=Suhaily Mohd|last3=Hamat|first3=Rukman Awang|last4=Jamaluddin|first4=Tengku Zetty Maztura Tengku|last5=Shafei|first5=Mohd Nazri|last6=Idris|first6=Norazlin|last7=Osman|first7=Malina|last8=Sukeri|first8=Surianti|last9=Wahab|first9=Zainudin A.|last10=Mohammad|first10=Wan Mohd Zahiruddin Wan|last11=Idris|first11=Zawaha|year=2018|title=Seroprevalence and distribution of leptospirosis serovars among wet market workers in northeastern, Malaysia: a cross sectional study|journal=BMC Infectious Diseases|language=en|volume=18|issue=1|pages=569|doi=10.1186/s12879-018-3470-5|issn=1471-2334|pmc=6236877|pmid=30428852}}</ref>\n\nChinese environmentalists, researchers and state media have called for stricter regulation of exotic animal trade in the markets.<ref name=\"BloombergAus\" /> Medical experts [[Zhong Nanshan]], [[Guan Yi]] and [[Yuen Kwok-yung]] have also called for the closure of wildlife markets since 2010.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/comment/opinion/article/3047828/first-sars-now-wuhan-coronavirus-heres-why-china-should-ban-its|title=Wuhan coronavirus another reason to ban China's wildlife trade forever|date=2020-01-29|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n=== COVID-19 ===\n\nAmidst the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Chinese wet markets have been blamed for the outbreak.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|last=Spinney|first=Laura|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/28/is-factory-farming-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Is factory farming to blame for coronavirus?|date=2020-03-28|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712|quote=Most of the attention so far has been focused on the interface between humans and the intermediate host, with fingers of blame being pointed at Chinese wet markets and eating habits,...}}</ref> Some reports say wildlife markets in other countries of Asia,<ref name=\"sierraclub.org\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9now.nine.com.au/60-minutes/coronavirus-expert-shut-down-of-asias-wet-wildlife-markets-60-minutes/f7f7781f-8e44-4eb8-9704-804b1e1680ca|title=Coronavirus expert calls for shut down of Asia's wildlife markets|last=|first=|date=|website=Nine News Australia|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5797739/wild-animals-markets-coronavirus/|title=Wild Animal Markets Spark Fear in Fight Against Coronavirus|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Africa,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wildaid.org/africa-risks-virus-outbreak-from-wildlife-trade/|title=Africa Risks Virus Outbreak From Wildlife Trade|date=2020-02-28|website=WildAid|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"dailymaverick\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-02-a-sea-change-in-chinas-attitude-towards-wildlife-exploitation-may-just-save-the-planet/|title=A sea change in China's attitude towards wildlife exploitation may just save the planet|date=2020-03-02|newspaper=Daily Maverick|quote=Knights hoped China would also play a role to help \u201ccountries around the world. It\u2019s no good simply banning the trade in China. The same risks are very much out there in Asia as well as Africa.\u201d}}</ref><ref name=\"indiamongabay\">{{cite news|url=https://india.mongabay.com/2020/03/commentary-crackdown-on-wet-markets-and-illegal-wildlife-trade-could-prevent-the-next-pandemic/|title=Crackdown on wet markets and illegal wildlife trade could prevent the next pandemic|date=2020-03-25|newspaper=Mongabay India|quote=...what we do know is that wet markets such as Wuhan, and for that matter Agartala\u2019s Golbazar or the thousands such that exist in Asia and Africa allow for easy transmission of viruses and other pathogens from animals to humans.}}</ref> and in general all over the world are also similarly prone to health risks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20200326/fact-check-is-chinese-culture-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Fact-check: Is Chinese culture to blame for the coronavirus?|last=Mekelburg|first=Madlin|website=Austin American-Statesman|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> In April 2020, a group of US lawmakers, [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases|NIAID]] director [[Anthony Fauci]], [[United Nations Environment Programme|UNEP]] biodiversity chief Elizabeth Maruma Mrema, and [[China Biodiversity Conservation and Green Development Foundation|CBCGDF]] secretary general Zhou Jinfeng called for the global closure of wildlife markets due to the potential for zoonotic diseases and risk to [[endangered species]].<ref name=\"Politico\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Greenfield|first=Patrick|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/06/ban-live-animal-markets-pandemics-un-biodiversity-chief-age-of-extinction|title=Ban wildlife markets to avert pandemics, says UN biodiversity chief|date=April 6, 2020|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=April 7, 2020|location=}}</ref><ref name=\"abc-april\">{{cite news|last=Fortier-Bensen|first=Tony|url=https://abcnews4.com/news/local/sen-lindsey-graham-among-others-urge-global-ban-of-live-wildlife-markets-and-trade|title=Sen. Lindsey Graham, among others, urge global ban of live wildlife markets and trade|date=9 April 2020|accessdate=9 April 2020|publisher=[[ABC News]]}}</ref>\n\n==Around the world==\n\n=== China ===\n[[File:Seafood section of Sanqi Baihui Market, Hall 1 (20190519152946).jpg|thumb|Seafood section of Sanqi Baihui Market in [[Beijing]], [[China]]]]\nIn 2018, wet markets were noted to have remained the most prevalent food outlet in urban regions of China despite the rise of [[List of supermarket chains in China|supermarket chains]] since the 1990s.<ref name=\"sustainability-2018\">{{Cite journal |last=Zhong |first=Taiyang |last2=Si |first2=Zhenzhong |last3=Crush |first3=Jonathan |last4=Xu |first4=Zhiying |last5=Huang |first5=Xianjin |last6=Scott |first6=Steffanie |last7=Tang |first7=Shuangshuang |last8=Zhang |first8=Xiang |year=2018 |title=The Impact of Proximity to Wet Markets and Supermarkets on Household Dietary Diversity in Nanjing City, China |url=http://www.mdpi.com/2071-1050/10/5/1465 |journal=Sustainability |language=en |volume=10 |issue=5 |pages=1465 |doi=10.3390/su10051465 |issn=2071-1050|doi-access=free }}</ref> However, wet markets have been losing ground in popularity compared to supermarkets, despite the fact they may be seen as healthier and more sustainable.<ref name=\"DavidFickling\">{{Cite news|last=Fickling|first=David|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-04-04/coronavirus-closing-china-s-wet-markets-isn-t-a-solution|title=China Is Reopening Its Wet Markets. That's Good|date=3 April 2020|work=Bloomberg|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Reports suggest \"although there are well-managed, hygienic wet markets in and near bigger cities [in China], hygiene can be spotty, especially in smaller communities.\"<ref name=\"BloombergAus\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-08/wuhan-is-returning-to-life-so-are-its-disputed-wet-markets|title=Wuhan Is Returning to Life. So Are Its Disputed Wet Markets|date=8 April 2020|work=Bloomberg Australia-NZ|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  During the 2010s, \"smart markets\" equipped with e-payment terminals emerged as traditional wet markets faced increasing competition from discount stores.<ref name=\"SD-Hangzhou\" /> Wet markets also began facing competition from online grocery stores, such as [[Alibaba]]'s Hema stores.<ref name=\"CNN-not\"/>\n\nSince the 1990s, large cities across China have moved traditional outdoor wet markets to modern indoor facilities.<ref name=\"HLZRZC\">{{Cite journal |last=Hu |first=Dong-wen |last2=Liu |first2=Chen-xing |last3=Zhao |first3=Hong-bo |last4=Ren |first4=Da-xi |last5=Zheng |first5=Xiao-dong |last6=Chen |first6=Wei |year=2019 |title=Systematic study of the quality and safety of chilled pork from wet markets, supermarkets, and online markets in China |url=http://link.springer.com/10.1631/jzus.B1800273 |journal=Journal of Zhejiang University-SCIENCE B |language=en |volume=20 |issue=1 |pages=95\u2013104 |doi=10.1631/jzus.B1800273 |issn=1673-1581 |pmc=6331336 |pmid=30614233}}</ref><ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/> In 1999, all roadside markets in [[Hangzhou]] were banned and moved indoors.<ref name=\"SD-Hangzhou\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.shine.cn/feature/travel/1805315493/ |publisher=[[Shanghai Daily]] |title=Regeneration and reinvention of Hangzhou's wet markets |last=Jia |first=Shi |date=31 May 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> By 2014, all wet markets in [[Nanjing]] were moved indoors.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/>\n\nThe [[trade of wildlife]] is not common in China, particularly in large cities,<ref name=\"CNN-not\"/> and most wet markets in China do not contain live animals besides fish held in tanks.<ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/> However, some poorly-regulated Chinese wet markets provide outlets for the exotic wildlife trade industry that was estimated to be worth more than $73 billion in a 2017 Chinese government report.<ref name=\"CNN-not\"/><ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/> In 2003, wet markets across China were banned from holding wildlife after the 2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak, which was directly tied to such practices.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2014, live poultry was banned from all markets in Hangzhou due to the [[Influenza A virus subtype H7N9#Reported cases in 2013|H7N9 avian influenza outbreak]].<ref name=\"SD-Hangzhou\" /> Although the exact origin of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] is yet to be confirmed as of April 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg24532764-000-the-hunt-for-patient-zero-where-did-the-coronavirus-outbreak-start/|title=The hunt for patient zero: Where did the coronavirus outbreak start?|last=Lu|first=Donna|website=New Scientist|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebulletin.org/2020/03/experts-know-the-new-coronavirus-is-not-a-bioweapon-they-disagree-on-whether-it-could-have-leaked-from-a-research-lab/|title=Experts know the new coronavirus is not a bioweapon. They disagree on whether it could have leaked from a research lab|date=2020-03-30|website=Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Readfearn |first=Graham |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/09/how-did-the-coronavirus-start-where-did-it-come-from-how-did-it-spread-humans-was-it-really-bats-pangolins-wuhan-animal-market |title=How did coronavirus start and where did it come from? Was it really Wuhan's animal market?|date=2020-04-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> it has been linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in [[Wuhan]], [[China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uchicagomedicine.org/forefront/prevention-and-screening-articles/wuhan-coronavirus|title=COVID-19: What we know so far about the 2019 novel coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Following the outbreak, epidemiology experts from China and an number of animal welfare organizations called to ban the operation of wet markets selling wild animals for human consumption.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://cbc.ca/radio/thecurrent/the-current-for-feb-17-2020-1.5466207/experts-call-for-global-ban-on-live-animal-markets-wildlife-trade-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak-1.5466219|title=Experts call for global ban on live animal markets, wildlife trade amidst coronavirus outbreak|date=February 17, 2020|work=CBC|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak|publisher=The Guardian|date=24 January 2020|title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak|author=Sarah Boseley}}</ref>\n\nThe Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market was shut down on 1 January 2020.<ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/> The Chinese government subsequently announced a temporary ban on the sale of wild animal products at wet markets in late January 2020,<ref name=\"sierraclub.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sierraclub.org/sierra/china-could-end-global-trade-wildlife|title=China Could End the Global Trade in Wildlife|date=2020-03-26|website=Sierra Club|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"BI-ban\">{{citation|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/china-bans-wildlife-trade-consumption-coronavirus-2020-2|publisher=Business Insider|date=25 February 2020|title=China just banned the trade and consumption of wild animals. Experts think the coronavirus jumped from live animals to people at a market. |first=Aylin |last=Woodward |quote=A few weeks later, Chinese authorities temporarily banned the buying, selling, and transportation of wild animals in markets, restaurants, and online marketplaces across the country. Farms that breed and transport wildlife were also quarantined and shut down. The ban was expected to stay in place until the coronavirus epidemic ended, Xinhua News reported. But now it's permanent. |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/> and then a permanent ban in February 2020 with an exception for [[Traditional Chinese medicine|Traditional Chinese Medicine]] ingredients.<ref name=\"BI-ban\"/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gorman|first=James|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/27/science/coronavirus-pangolin-wildlife-ban-china.html|title=China's Ban on Wildlife Trade a Big Step, but Has Loopholes, Conservationists Say|date=2020-02-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> By 22 March 2020, at least 94% of the temporarily closed wet markets in China were reopened according to Chinese state-run media,<ref name=\"CNN-not\"/><ref name=\"DavidFickling\"/> leading to public criticism of the Chinese government's handling of wet markets by [[Anthony Fauci]] and [[Lindsey Graham]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=O'reilly|first=Andrew|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/lindsey-graham-asks-china-to-close-all-operating-wet-markets-after-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Lindsey Graham asks China to close 'all operating wet markets' after coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-04-02|work=Fox News|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bowden|first=John|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/490834-graham-asks-colleagues-to-support-call-for-china-to-close-wet-markets|title=Graham asks colleagues to support call for China to close wet markets|date=2020-04-02|work=The Hill|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/03/anthony-fauci-foreign-wet-markets-shutdown-162975 |title='Shut down those things right away': Calls to close 'wet markets' ramp up pressure on China |first=Quint |last=Forgey |date=3 April 2020 |work=Politico |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> As of April 2020, the Chinese government is drafting a permanent law to further tighten restrictions on wildlife trade.<ref name=\"CNN-not\"/><ref name=\"Guardian-Standaert\"/>\n\n=== Hong Kong ===\n[[File:HK Bridges Street Market.JPG|thumb|The building that housed the former [[Bridges Street Market]] in [[Hong Kong]]]]\n[[File:Allmart (Shui Chuen O) Market.jpg|thumb|Shui Chuen O Market, a newer wet market under the ownership of the [[Hong Kong Housing Authority]]]]\n\nOn 16 May 1842, [[Central Market, Hong Kong|Central Market]] was opened in a central position on Queen's Road. In this market, people could find all kinds of meat, fruit and vegetables, poultry, salt fish, fresh fish, weighing rooms and money changers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/g1842/728468.pdf|title=The Friend Of China, and Hong Kong Gazette|date=1842-05-12|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 1920, the Reclamation Street Market was opened in [[Hong Kong]]. Due to structure problems, Reclamation Street Market was removed by the government in 1953.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u7b2c\u4e8c\u5c46\u5eff\u4e00\u4e16\u7d00\u83ef\u4eba\u5730\u5340\u6b77\u53f2\u6559\u80b2\u8ad6\u6587\u96c6|trans-title=Second Collection of Historical Education Papers on Chinese in the 21st Century |author=Bao Shaolin|publisher=Zhonghua Book Company (Hong Kong) Limited.|year=2012|language=Chinese|isbn=|location=|pages=332}}</ref> In 1957, Yau Ma Tei Street Market launched to replace the Reclamation Street Market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmis.hkpl.gov.hk/coverpage/-/coverpage/view?p_r_p_-1078056564_c=QF757YsWv59a9PNz3lScYjii24oro5jB&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_o=18&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_actual_q=%28%20%28%20allTermsMandatory%3A%28true%29%20OR+all_dc.title%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.creator%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.contributor%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.subject%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+fulltext%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.description%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20%29%20%29&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_order=desc&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_field=score&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_log=Y|title=\u6cb9\u9ebb\u5730\u65b0\u5efa\u8857\u5e02\u6628\u6668\u958b\u5e55\u5f8c\u71df\u696d|trans-title=Yau Ma Tei New Market opened after opening yesterday morning|language=Chinese|last=|first=|date=1957-11-02|work=Hong Kong Business Daily|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> There were fixed-pitch stalls which sold vegetables, fruits, seafood, beef, pork, and poultry. Also, there were stalls selling baby chickens, baby ducks, and three-striped box turtles as pets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hkmemory.hk/collections/oral_history/All_Items_OH/oha_70/records/index.html|title=Yau Ma Tei's wet markets in the early post-war period|date=2011-03-29|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, wet markets accounted for 70% of produce sales and 50% of meat sales in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"ATH-7\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq |title=Agricultural Trade Highlights |publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]] |year=1994 |page=7}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2000, many of Hong Kong's wet markets were managed by the [[Urban Council]] (within Hong Kong Island and Kowloon) or the [[Regional Council (Hong Kong)|Regional Council]] (in the [[New Territories]]). Since the disbandment of the two councils on 31 December 1999, these markets have been managed by the [[Food and Environmental Hygiene Department]] (FEHD) of the Hong Kong government.<ref name=\"2018fehd\" /><ref name=\"hk-audit\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aud.gov.hk/pdf_e/e51ch06sum.pdf |title=Report No. 51 of the Director of Audit \u2014 Chapter 6 |publisher=[[Audit Commission (Hong Kong)|Audit Commission]] |date=November 2008 |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 the government of Hong Kong proposed that all poultry should be slaughtered at central abattoirs to combat the spread of [[avian flu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.news.gov.hk/isd/ebulletin/en/category/issues/080614/html/080613en05005.htm |title=Central abattoir set for 2011 |website=Archive.news.gov.hk |date=2008-06-13 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the FEHD operated 74 wet markets housing approximately 13,070 stalls.<ref name=\"2018fehd\">{{cite web |title=Chapter IV \u2013 Environmental Hygiene |url=https://www.fehd.gov.hk/english/publications/annualrpt/2018/4.html |website=Annual Report 2018 |publisher=Food and Environmental Hygiene Department}}</ref> In addition, the [[Hong Kong Housing Authority]] operated 21 markets while private developers operated about 99 (in 2017).<ref name=\"legco2017\">{{cite web |title=Public markets |url=https://www.legco.gov.hk/research-publications/english/1617issh36-public-markets-20170927-e.pdf |publisher=Legislative Council Secretariat |date=27 September 2017}}</ref> As of 2018, planning is underway for new wet markets in the new towns at Tung Chung, Tin Shui Wai, Hung Shui Kiu, Tseung Kwan O, and Kwu Tung North.<ref name=\"2018fehd\" />\n\nIn Hong Kong, wet markets are most frequented by older residents, those with lower incomes, and domestic helpers who serve approximately 10 percent of Hong Kong's residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emeraldinsight.com/journals.htm?articleid=1412265&show=abstract |title=EmeraldInsight |website=EmeraldInsight.com |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Most [[Districts of Hong Kong|districts]] contain at least one wet market.<ref name=\"CNN-not\"/> Wet markets have become destinations for tourists to \"see the real Hong Kong\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://intransit.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/18/a-guide-to-hong-kongs-wet-markets/ | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | first=Sei | last=Chong | title=A Guide to Hong Kong's Wet Markets | date=18 March 2011|accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Many of the wet market buildings are owned by property investment firms and as a result the price of food can vary from market to market.<ref>{{cite news|author=Elmer W. Cagape |url=http://asiancorrespondent.com/64501/expensive-food-tung-chung-hk/ |title=Tung Chung town pays the most for food in Hong Kong |work=Asian Correspondent |date=2011-09-08 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Hong Kong's wet markets are known to use red lampshades to make the food look fresher.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u8d85\u5de8\u8857\u5e02\u71c8\u73fe\u8eab\u5546\u5834|trans-title=Super large wet market red lamps appears in shopping mall|url=http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|accessdate=19 November 2012|newspaper=Sharp Daily|date=14 September 2012|language=Chinese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108070308/http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|archive-date=8 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMarkets in Hong Kong are governed by the [[law of Hong Kong]], not [[Chinese law]]. Under the Slaughterhouse Regulation, the slaughtering of live bovine animals, swine, goats, sheep or soliped for human consumption must take place in a licenced slaughterhouse.<ref name=\"slaughterhousereg\">{{cite web |title=Cap. 132BU Slaughterhouses Regulation |url=https://www.elegislation.gov.hk/hk/cap132BU |website=Hong Kong e-Legislation |publisher=[[Department of Justice (Hong Kong)|Department of Justice]]}}</ref> None of the wet markets in Hong Kong hold wild or exotic animals.<ref name=\"CNN-not\"/>\n\nThe retail sale of live poultry in Hong Kong is permitted at licenced outlets only. At the end of 2016, there were 85 retail shops within public wet markets licenced to sell live poultry.<ref name=\"2017fhb\">{{cite web |title=Study on the Way Forward of Live Poultry Trade in Hong Kong |url=https://www.fhb.gov.hk/download/press_and_publications/consultation/170403_f_live_poultry_trade/e_consultancy_report_full.pdf |publisher=[[Food and Health Bureau]] |date=March 2017}}</ref> The FEHD has implemented a number of measures to reduce the risk of [[avian influenza]]. Regular inspections and cleaning take place, including nightly disinfection of each stall by external contractors. Stall owners selling live poultry are not allowed to keep the animals on the premises overnight; they must be slaughtered before 8:00 pm nightly.<ref name=\"2016fehd\">{{cite web |title=Faecal droppings of live poultry from Yan Oi Market in Tuen Mun tested positive of H7N9 virus |url=https://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201606/05/P201606050090.htm |publisher=Hong Kong Government |date=5 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Indonesia===\nTraditional wet markets (such as [[pasar pagi]]) are found across in [[Indonesia]] in both urban and rural areas. Wet markets face increasing competition from supermarkets as well as e-commerce companies like [[Shopee]] and [[Tokopedia]].<ref name=\"Nikkei\">{{cite news |url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Life-Arts/Life/Southeast-Asia-s-traditional-markets-hold-their-own |last=Roughneen |first=Simon |title=Southeast Asia's traditional markets hold their own |publisher=[[The Nikkei|Nikkei Asian Review]] |date=8 October 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In 2018, Indonesian wet market vendors that import goods expressed concerns over the decrease in value of the [[Indonesian rupiah]].<ref name=\"Nikkei\" />\n\nMany urban wet markets have undergone major renovations during the last decade, such as Jakarta's [[Mayestik Market]], to modernize them by introducing air conditioning, better ventilation, improved rubbish and liquid disposal systems, improved hygiene, and more safe and comfortable facilities for sellers.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} In 2018, the first modern wet market opened in [[Jakarta]] with a laboratory as well as freezing and refrigeration facilities.<ref name=\"Nikkei\" />\n\n===Malaysia===\nIn March 2020, the Malaysian government temporarily banned the operation of all wet markets (including ''[[pasar malam]]'' and ''pasar pagi'') as a [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia|national response to the coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"malaysia-ban\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/22/negri-hawkers-food-trucks-to-operate-7am-8pm-from-march-24 |publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]] |title=Negri hawkers, food trucks to operate 7am-8pm from March 24 |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\n[[File:Mercado 20 de noviembre - Oaxaca de Ju\u00e1rez - 10.jpg|thumb|Fresh meat section of the Mercado 20 de Noviembre in [[Oaxaca City|Oaxaca]], [[Mexico]]]]\nSome traditional [[Mexico|Mexican]] open-air markets called ''[[tianguis]]'', such as the Mercado Margarita Maza de Ju\u00e1rez in [[Oaxaca City|Oaxaca]], are separated into a wet market (''zona h\u00fameda'') and a dry market (''zona seca'').<ref name=\"imparcial\">{{cite news |url=https://imparcialoaxaca.mx/oaxaca/304648/central-de-abasto-bomba-de-tiempo-y-nido-de-delincuencia/ |title=Central de Abasto: bomba de tiempo y nido de delincuencia |publisher=[[El Imparcial (Oaxaca)]] |date=9 May 2019 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Philippines===\n{{Main|Palengke}}\nIn the [[Philippines]], wet markets are managed by [[cooperative]]s according to legislation such as the [[Philippine legal codes#Some other legal codes|Cooperatives Code]] (RA 7160) and the [[Agriculture and Fisheries Modernization Act of 1997|Agriculture and Fisheries Modernization Act]] (RA 8435).<ref name=\"PCIJ2002\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcij.org/imag/Society/palengke.html|title=Death of the Palengke|last=Pabico|first=Alecks P.|year=2002|publisher=Philippine Center for Investigative Journalism|accessdate=2009-01-05}}</ref> The Philippine government has control over the price of some commodities sold in palengkes, especially critical foods such as [[rice]].<ref name=\"Inq20080328\">{{cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/regions/view/20080328-127024/6-Cebu-rice-retailers-suspended-for-violations|title=6 Cebu rice retailers suspended for violations |last=Napallacan|first=Jhunnex|date=2008-03-28|work=Breaking News / Regions|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref><ref name=\"SS20070421\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/zam/2007/04/21/bus/food.agency.intensifies.palengke.watch..html|title=Food agency intensifies 'Palengke Watch'|last=Garcia|first=Bong|date=2007-04-21|publisher=Sun.Star Zamboanga|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, the digital wet market Palengke Boy was launched in [[Davao City]] to compete against traditional wet markets.<ref name=\"sunstar\">{{cite news |url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/1763228 |title=Teves: Palengke Boy: The family's digital wet market buddy |last=Huang-Teves |first=Janette |publisher=[[Sun.Star]] |date=7 September 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In March 2020, the [[Pasig]] local government launched a mobile wet market to ensure access to basic goods during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"abs-cbn\">{{cite news |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/26/20/taking-cue-from-pasig-valenzuela-eyes-own-market-on-wheels-amid-quarantine |title=Taking cue from Pasig, Valenzuela eyes own market-on-wheels amid quarantine |last=Domingo |first=Katrina |publisher=[[ABS-CBN]] |date=26 March 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Singapore===\n[[File:Wet market in Tekka Centre, Singapore - 20030228.jpg|thumb|Wet market in [[Tekka Centre|Tekka Market]], [[Singapore]]]]\nWet markets in [[Singapore]] are subsidized by the government.<ref name=\"Nikkei\" /> The [[Tekka Centre|Tekka Market]], [[Tiong Bahru#Tiong Bahru Market|Tiong Bahru Market]], and [[Chinatown, Singapore#Geography|Chinatown Complex Market]] are prominent wet markets containing seasonal fruit, fresh vegetables, imported beef, and live seafood.<ref name=\"cnn-sg\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/singapore-wet-market/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |title=Singapore wet markets: Reminder of bygone days |date=22 June 2015 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, the slaughter of animals was banned in 12 inner-city markets and 22 wet market centers in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RjxIAAAAYAAJ |title=U.S. Trade and Prospects: Dairy, livestock, and poultry products |year=1992 |publisher=The Service |author=United States. Foreign Agricultural Service. Dairy, Livestock, and Poultry Division, United States. World Agricultural Outlook Board |page=3}}</ref> In early 2020, the [[National Environment Agency]] issued advisories for \"high standards of hygiene and cleanliness\" for the 83 markets that it oversees in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore#Preventive measures|a response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|last=Chandran|first=Rina|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/southeast-asia-health-markets/traditional-markets-blamed-for-virus-outbreak-are-lifeline-for-asias-poor-idUSL8N2A5201|title=Traditional markets blamed for virus outbreak are lifeline for Asia's poor|date=7 February 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n===Taiwan===\nIn 1997, a report by the [[Taipei]] city government indicated that the city had 61 major wet markets with almost 10,000 registered vendors.<ref name=\"twt\">{{cite news |url=https://taiwantoday.tw/news.php?post=12589&unit=8,29,32,45 |title=Are Wet Markets Drying Up? |publisher=[[Taiwan Today]] |last=Trappey |first=Charles V. |date=1 March 1997 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The report also indicated that most of the city's wet markets were in serious need of repair and that almost 3,500 of the vendor stalls lay vacant.<ref name=\"twt\" />\n\nThe Nanmen Market in Taipei is a government-owned traditional wet market that was opened in 1907 during the [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|Japanese colonial rule]].<ref name=\"focus\">{{cite news |publisher=[[Focus Taiwan]] |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/business/201910060010 |title=Nanmen Market to close for renovation after 38 years |date=6 October 2019 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"twt\" /> The market building was demolished in October 2019 and the market temporarily relocated until its replacement modern 12-floor building is completed in 2022.<ref name=\"focus\" />\n\n===Thailand===\n{{multiimage\n|direction=horizontal\n|image1=Wet market Chiang Mai.jpg\n|image2=Wet market Chiang Mai 2.jpg\n|width1=130\n|width2=215\n|footer=A wet market in Chinatown, [[Chiang Mai]], Thailand, selling a variety of shellfish and turtles.}}\n\nWet markets are the dominant preferred venue for grocery shopping in [[Thailand]] due to the local importance of fresh food,<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=-A-7d-2VpwcC |page=295 |title= Consumer Behavior and Culture: Consequences for Global Marketing and Advertising  |first=Marieke |last=de Mooij |publisher=[[Chronicle Books]] |year=2003|isbn=9780761926689 }}</ref> as well as lower prices and familiarity with shopkeepers.<ref name=\"Nikkei\" />\n\n===Vietnam===\nIn 2017, there were approximately 9,000 wet markets, 800 supermarkets, 160 shopping malls and 1.3 million small family-owned stores across [[Vietnam]] according to government estimates.<ref name=\"vne\">{{cite news |url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/travel-life/a-hanoi-wet-market-at-the-crossroads-of-modernity-3588516.html |publisher=[[VnExpress]] |title=A Hanoi wet market at the crossroads of modernity |last=Yen |first=Bao |date=12 June 2017 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the [[Hanoi]] city government planned to renovate the city's wet markets and transform them into modern shopping malls.<ref name=\"vne\" /> The plan was met with resistance from wet market vendors in 2017 after significant declines in sales figures from other markets that were moved to the basements of high-end shopping centers.<ref name=\"vne\" />\n\nIn 2020, [[Prime Minister of Vietnam]] [[Nguy\u1ec5n Xu\u00e2n Ph\u00fac]] announced proposals to ban wildlife trade in Vietnam.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Media coverage==\n\n{{globalize section|date=April 2020}}\n<!-- This section is for content *about* media coverage of wet markets, not content *from* media coverage of wet markets -->\nChinese wet markets have been criticized in media outlets during the COVID-19 outbreak.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nIn [[Western media]] wet markets have been portrayed without distinguishing between general wet markets, live animal wet markets, and wildlife markets,<ref name=\"BloombergAus\" /> using montages of images from different markets across China without identifying locations.<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\">{{cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/why-shutting-down-chinese-wet-markets-could-be-a-terrible-mistake-130625|title=Why shutting down Chinese 'wet markets' could be a terrible mistake|last1=Lynteris|first1=Christos|last2=Fearnley|first2=Lyle|date=2 March 2020|publisher=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lat\">{{cite news|last=St. Cavendish|first=Christopher|url=https://www.latimes.com/food/story/2020-03-11/coronavirus-china-wet-markets|title=No, China's fresh food markets did not cause coronavirus|date=11 March 2020|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> Most wet markets in China do not sell wild animals.<ref name=\"DavidFickling\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radiichina.com/wet-markets-wild-animals-china/|title=No, You Won't Find \"Wild Animals\" in Most of China's Wet Markets|last=Bossons|first=Matthew|date=2020-02-25|website=RADII|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/> These depictions have been criticized as exaggerated and [[Orientalism|Orientalist]], and have been blamed for fueling [[Sinophobia]] and \"Chinese otherness\".<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\" /><ref name=\"lat\" /><ref name=\"FP\" />\n\nSince the outbreak of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], media reports urging for permanent blanket bans on all wet markets\u2014as opposed to solely live animal markets or wildlife markets\u2014have been criticized for undermining [[infection control]] needs to be specific about wildlife markets, such as the Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market.<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Artisanal food]]\n* [[Asian supermarket]]\n* [[Bazaar]]\n* [[Pasar malam]]\n* [[Souk]]\n* [[Ye wei]] (southern China)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Wet markets}}\n{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/gallery/2009/may/15/china-animalwelfare-cat | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Conservation (Environment), Wildlife (Environment), World news, China (News), Animal welfare (News), Food (impact of production on environment), Animals (News), Ethical and green living (Environment), Environment, Chinese food and drink, Asia Pacific (News) | date=15 May 2009}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:Food markets]]\n[[Category:Retail markets]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1001:b011:e03a:e9ab:5a56:801a:3925", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wet_market"}
{"title_page": "The Berenstain Bears (2003 TV series)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|The Berenstain Bears (1985 TV series)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name          = The Berenstain Bears\n|image              =\n|caption            =\n|camera             = \n|picture_format     = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n|audio_format       = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n|runtime            = 30 minutes\n|genre              = [[Children's television series|Children's series]]<br>[[Educational]]\n|creator            = [[Stan and Jan Berenstain]] \n|executive_producer = Stan and Jan Berenstain<br>Steven Ching<br>Scott Dyer<br>[[Michael Hirsh (producer)|Michael Hirsh]]\n|producer           = Lan Lamon<br>''Supervising producers:''<br>Patricia R. Burns<br>Jocelyn Hamilton<br>Michelle Melanson<br>Cynthia Taylor\n|voices             = [[Camilla Scott]]<br>[[Benedict Campbell|Ben Campbell]]<br>[[Michael Cera]]<br>[[Tajja Isen]]<br>[[Corinne Conley]]<br>Leslie Carlson<br>Amanda Soha<br>Marc McCulkin\n|narrated           =  \n|theme_music_composer = Stan Meissner\n|opentheme          = \"The Berenstain Bears\" by [[Lee Ann Womack]]\n|endtheme           = \"The Berenstain Bears\" (Instrumental)\n|composer          = Ray Parker<br>Tom Szczesniak\n|company            = [[Nelvana|Nelvana Limited]]<br>AGOGO Entertainment\n|country            = Canada\n|language           = English\n|network            = [[PBS Kids]] (US)<br>[[Treehouse TV]] (Canada)\n|first_aired        = {{Start date|2003|1|6}}\n|last_aired         = {{End date|2004|12|6}}\n|num_seasons        = 3\n|num_episodes       = 40\n|list_episodes      = List of The Berenstain Bears (2003 TV series) episodes\n|preceded_by        = [[The Berenstain Bears (1985 TV series)|''The Berenstain Bears'' (1985 TV series)]]\n|website            = http://www.berenstainbears.com \n}}\n\n'''''The Berenstain Bears''''' is a Canadian children's [[animated series|animated]] [[television comedy]] series based on the [[Berenstain Bears|children's book series of the same name]] by [[Stan and Jan Berenstain]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=77-78}}</ref> The series follows the lives of a family of [[anthropomorphic]] [[bear]]s who learn a [[moral]] or [[safety]]-related lesson during the course of each episode. It ran for forty episodes in three seasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Berenstain Bears|url=http://www.nelvana.com/show/116/berenstain-bears|publisher=Corus Entertainment|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref> The series debuted on [[PBS Kids]] in the United States on January 6, 2003 and ended on December 6, 2004.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}} Reruns continued to air on PBS Kids until September 2, 2007.\n\n[[The Berenstain Bears (1985 TV series)|A previous ''Berenstain Bears'' cartoon]] aired in Australia and the United States from 1985 to 1987.\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe series is set in a world populated solely by anthropomorphic bears and primarily centers around the Berenstain Bears. The Berenstain Bears are a family residing in the rural community of Bear Country consisting of Mama Bear, Papa Bear, Brother Bear, and Sister Bear. Albeit numerous episodes are based on the books and promote the same morals as encouraged in the picture books from which their plots originated, the program's faithfulness to the original series is slightly mixed on account of a number of later episodes following original storylines. Nonetheless, they mostly portray the same environment depicted in the original ''Berenstain Bears'' storybooks quite accurately and concentrate on the messages and lessons learned by the family through their different experiences, such as generousity and responsibility, as well as the daily lives of the bears.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Main|List of The Berenstain Bears (2003 TV series) episodes}}\n{{:List of The Berenstain Bears (2003 TV series) episodes}}\n\n==Cast and characters==\n\n===Main===\n*[[Michael Cera]] as Brother Bear (Episodes 1-26)\n*[[Michael D'Ascenzo]] as Brother Bear (Episodes 27-40)\n*[[Tajja Isen]] as Sister Bear\n*[[Benedict Campbell]] as Papa Q. Bear\n*[[Camilla Scott]] as Mama Bear\n\n===Recurring===\n\n====Family====\n*[[Leslie Carlson]] as Grizzly Gramps \n*[[Corinne Conley]] as Grizzly Gran\n*[[Marc McMulkin]] as Cousin Freddy\n\n====Friends====\n*Amanda Soha as Lizzy Bruin\n*Nikki Marshall as Queenie\n*[[Mark Rendall]] as Ferdy Factual\n*Gage Knox as Too-Tall\n*Patrick Salvagna as Skuzz\n*[[James Eckhouse (Canadian actor)|James Eckhouse]] as Smirk\n\n====Citizens====\n*[[Chris Wiggins]] as Squire Grizzly\n*Ellen-Ray Hennessy as Miss Grizzle\n*[[Philip Williams (actor)|Philip Williams]] as Farmer Ben\n\n==Production==\nThe show was produced by the Canadian [[animation]] company [[Nelvana]] for [[PBS Kids]] in the United States and [[Treehouse TV]] in Canada. Eighty 15-minute episodes were produced, adapted from the books and also a few new stories as well, similar to the 1985 production.<ref name=gillies>{{cite news|author=Gillies, Judith S.|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-01-04/news/0301040264_1_stan-berenstain-berenstain-bears-bears-titles|title=Grin 'n' 'Bear' it: The Berenstains come to WTTW|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=January 4, 2003|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref> However, due to Canadian laws requiring Nelvana to employ only Canadian writers and artists, the Berenstains' involvement in the program was limited; They sought to exert their influence on some details, according to Stan. \"Our bears don't wear shoes, and Papa wouldn't wear his hat in the house...And we try to keep complete, total banality out of the stories.\" Common practicalities of animation did force some minor costume changes from the books, such as eliminating polka dots and plaids. (This issue also occurred in the previous animated series and specials. Only a limited amount of polka dots was allowed in the five specials.)<ref name=\"gillies\"/> The show's theme song is performed by [[Lee Ann Womack]].<ref name=gillies/> The series is supposed to supplement the 1985 series because new books were released since then, even though the two series have a radically different production style as well as a change of in-universe elements. Another issue is the two series are never seen together.\n\n===Music===\nCountry music singer-songwriter [[Lee Ann Womack]] sings the series' theme song, which was written by [[Stan Meissner]].\n\n==Broadcast==\nIt debuted in the United States on PBS Kids on January 6, 2003.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Berenstain Bears \u2013 The Nelvana-Produced Series Comes To Video For The First Time Ever|url=http://www.corusent.com/news/the-berenstain-bears-the-nelvana-produced-series-comes-to-video-for-the-first-time-ever/|publisher=Corus Entertainment Inc.|accessdate=29 April 2018|date=December 10, 2002}}</ref> Originally, it aired together with ''[[Seven Little Monsters (TV series)|Seven Little Monsters]]'' but the two shows were eventually separated.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Berenstain Bears Bring 40 Years Of Literary History To \"PBS Kids\" With Premiere Of 15-Minute Animated TV Series|url=http://www.corusent.com/news/the-berenstain-bears%c2%a8-bring-40-years-of-literary-history-to-pbs-kids-with-premiere-of-15-minute-animated-tv-series/|publisher=Corus Entertainment|date=November 14, 2002|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref> It also ran on [[Knowledge Network|Knowledge]] (British Columbia), [[CITV]],  [[Tiny Pop]] and [[KidsCo]] (UK), OBS (South Korea), [[YTV (TV channel)|YTV]], [[Treehouse TV]], [[Nickelodeon (Canadian TV channel)|Nickelodeon]] and [[Teletoon Retro]] in Canada. The show also broadcasts reruns on PBS Kids Sprout from the channel's inception until the network rebranded into [[Universal Kids]].\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Recipients and nominees\n!Outcome\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2004\n|[[Gemini Award]]s\n|Best Pre-School Program or Series\n|[[Stan and Jan Berenstain|Stan Berenstain, Jan Berenstain]], [[Michael Hirsh (producer)|Michael Hirsh]], Steven Ching, Scott Dyer\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|style=\"white-space:nowrap;\"|[[Young Artist Award]]s\n|style=\"white-space:nowrap;\"|Best Performance in a Voice-Over Role \u2013 Young Actress\n|[[Tajja Isen]]\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb title|0364793|The Berenstain Bears}}\n*{{tv.com show|the-berenstain-bears|The Berenstain Bears}}\n{{Berenstain Bears}}\n{{PBS Kids shows}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berenstain Bears (2002 TV series), The}}\n[[Category:Canadian children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2000s Canadian animated television series]]\n[[Category:2003 Canadian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2004 Canadian television series endings]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Berenstain Bears]]\n[[Category:Canadian television programs based on children's books]]\n[[Category:Canadian preschool education television series]]\n[[Category:PBS original programming]]\n[[Category:Canadian animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Television series by Nelvana]]\n[[Category:PBS Kids shows]]\n[[Category:Treehouse TV shows]]\n[[Category:YTV shows]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about bears]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about families]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about siblings]]\n[[Category:Canadian television series with live action and animation]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|The Berenstain Bears (1985 TV series)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name          = The Berenstain Bears\n|image              =\n|caption            =\n|camera             = \n|picture_format     = [